{"term":"1970","caseName":"Citizens To Preserve Overton Park v. Volpe","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1970/1066","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 11, 1971","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger2/oral_argument_audio/16520","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Citizens to Preserve Overton Park against Volpe, Mr. Vardaman you may proceed whenever you are ready.","start":0,"stop":10.292,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court.","start":10.292,"stop":14.359,"duration":4.07},{"text":"This case was previously before Your Honors on December 7, at which time the parties engaged in extensive oral argument on petitioner's application for stay to prevent the construction of a large six-lane interstate highway through Overton Park in Memphis Tennessee.","start":14.359,"stop":34.489,"duration":20.13},{"text":"After hearing argument, the Court granted the stay, granted certiorari, set the case for argument on the merits today.","start":34.489,"stop":43.978,"duration":9.49},{"text":"As Your Honors will recall, this case arises under a federal statute, generally, referred to as Section 4 (f) of the Department of Transportation Act which provides that the Secretary of Transportation shall not approve a highway project which affects a public park such as Overton Park, unless there are no feasible and prudent alternative routes or unless the design includes all possible planning to minimize harm.","start":43.978,"stop":77.524,"duration":33.55},{"text":"As we pointed out in the argument on December the 7, there are all alternative routes to that through the park, there are all alternative designs which would minimize harm to the park, designs admittedly possible in this case.","start":77.524,"stop":93.906,"duration":16.38},{"text":"We have alleged supported that the proper determinations which are required by Section 4 (f) of the Department of Transportation Act, were not made and indeed even if they were made, they were infirm or legally invalid.","start":93.906,"stop":113.031,"duration":19.13},{"text":"Since this Court granted certiorari, there have been two important developments in this case.","start":113.031,"stop":119.61,"duration":6.58},{"text":"Immediately thereafter, the Solicitor General on behalf of the Secretary, filed a motion to remand in which he conceded that the courts below had erred in granting and affirming summary judgment on the basis of affidavits which merely characterize documents on which these determinations, he said, had been made.","start":119.61,"stop":143.225,"duration":23.61},{"text":"We certainly agree that the summary judgment was wrong, but we have oppose an immediate remand because of the other important issues which we believe should be decided in this case.","start":143.225,"stop":154.105,"duration":10.88},{"text":"The second important development which has occurred since we were here before, occurred approximately 10 minutes ago.","start":154.105,"stop":162.225,"duration":8.12},{"text":"At that time, the Solicitor General handed me two pieces of paper, which purport to be affidavits which I understand he is attempting to file in this case at this time, one of which says that as an affidavit of Alan S. Boyd and which he says as a matter of fact that he did make the determination which we have alleged he did not make and which we have offered to prove that he did not make.","start":162.225,"stop":189.23,"duration":27},{"text":"The second piece of paper which he has filed purports to be an affidavit of John Volpe that he made certain determinations.","start":189.23,"stop":197.83,"duration":8.6},{"text":"Now I know that no president which permits a party to filed in this Court, at this stage in the proceedings affidavit.","start":197.83,"stop":206.688,"duration":8.86},{"text":"I do recall that there was a case here, I believe in 1968 entitled Bumpers against North Carolina, in which the case, in which this Court, it granted certiorari to consider the validity of a warrantless search.","start":206.688,"stop":222.12,"duration":15.43},{"text":"And as I recall that case during the course of the oral argument, the attorney for the state said for the first time in the proceedings that in fact the search in that case had not been without a warrant, that he had found the warrant after the decision below and I believe he attempted to file the warrant in this court.","start":222.12,"stop":242.248,"duration":20.13},{"text":"As I recall the opinion in that case, the Court said, it's too late.","start":242.248,"stop":245.714,"duration":3.47},{"text":"You make your record in a trial court and at that point you consider that's where these facts are tried out.","start":245.714,"stop":251.752,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you familiar with the case Giles against Maryland?","start":251.752,"stop":257.863,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Generally, I am not familiar with any aspect that would bear on this point.","start":257.863,"stop":264.492,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is a big aspect that bears very directly on this point.","start":264.492,"stop":268.895,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps if the Court would like, memorandum on whether this evidence is properly before the Court at this time, I would be happy to file a memorandum, but I think that this is an extraordinary effort in which -- the manner in which to present evidence in a case, particularly since we were not permitted, in fact, the Court of Appeals held that we were barred by this Court's decision in Morgan from taking a deposition which we had specifically offered, will dispute one of these affidavits.","start":268.895,"stop":308.599,"duration":39.7},{"text":"If as we submit one of the crucial issues in this case, is whether the determinations under Section 49 (f) of the Department of Transportation Act have been made.","start":308.599,"stop":319.97,"duration":11.37},{"text":"We think that it's undisputed that that is a crucial issue in this case then that issue should be tired out in the way disputed issues in fact are traditionally tried in lawsuit.","start":319.97,"stop":330.844,"duration":10.87},{"text":"We should put on our evidence and they should put theirs on.","start":330.844,"stop":334.129,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Each side's evidence should be subject to cross examination.","start":334.129,"stop":337.688,"duration":3.56},{"text":"We should not try it up by affidavits filed in this Court.","start":337.688,"stop":342.9,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"These paper will be lodged and the Court will determine their posture at a latter date and if we need anything from you Mr. Vardaman will then indicate to you that -- we'll invite you come and offer it.","start":342.9,"stop":355.473,"duration":12.57}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":355.473,"stop":357.724,"duration":2.25},{"text":"With respect to -- I might add that in my review of these documents at the time before they were filed indicates to me that they do not fulfill the requirements of the department, the transportation order which was as I understand promulgated on October 7, 1970, which now requires formal findings, in cases under Section 4 (f) of the Department of Transportation Act.","start":357.724,"stop":385.122,"duration":27.4},{"text":"So even if the Court were consider, to consider this evidence the Secretary has still not complied with that order.","start":385.122,"stop":393.663,"duration":8.54},{"text":"And I think under this courts decision in the Thorpe case, where it states the general rule that the issues presented here must be determined in accordance with the law as it existed at the time of decision.","start":393.663,"stop":407.103,"duration":13.44},{"text":"Even if you consider these pieces of paper it would still not be compliance with that order, or with the law and a remand would be necessary.","start":407.103,"stop":418.9,"duration":11.8},{"text":"The second issue which remains in this case, aside from the question of whether there was adequate compliance with Section 4 (f) by the Secretary's failure to render any written document at the time the decision was made, the second issue which remains is whether, whether the court below was proper in holding that petitioners were barred from deposing formal Federal Highway Administrator, Bridwell in order to determine whether or not the decisions under this Statute were made.","start":418.9,"stop":453.047,"duration":34.15},{"text":"And we sought to depose formal Federal Highway Administrator, Bridwell because the documents in this case indicate that if he wasn't the sole person who made the determinations at least he was intimately involved in any determination that would have been made.","start":453.047,"stop":469.035,"duration":15.99},{"text":"Indeed the record never refers, at least, until these documents submitted today there was no reference in the record to decision made by former secretary Boyd.","start":469.035,"stop":481.085,"duration":12.05},{"text":"Wherever his name appeared, it appeared jointly with Federal Highway Administrator Bridwell.","start":481.085,"stop":486.219,"duration":5.13},{"text":"More over it was Mr. Bridwell who went to Congress to testify about what occurred in this case.","start":486.219,"stop":491.696,"duration":5.48},{"text":"So we noticed the deposition of Mr. Bridwell.","start":491.696,"stop":494.164,"duration":2.47},{"text":"We have offered to prove through his deposition that no such determination was made.","start":494.164,"stop":499.154,"duration":4.99},{"text":"That in fact, he merely delegated this to City Council of Memphis and left it up to them to decide.","start":499.154,"stop":505.932,"duration":6.78},{"text":"The Court of Appeals said that this Court's decision in Morgan against United States prohibited any interrogation of the Secretary as to determine whether or not he made these decisions.","start":505.932,"stop":519.955,"duration":14.02},{"text":"We believe that that is erroneous extension of the Morgan Doctrine.","start":519.955,"stop":523.585,"duration":3.63},{"text":"While Morgan may prohibit inquiry as to how decisions were made it does not.","start":523.585,"stop":529.263,"duration":5.68},{"text":"I believe this Court's decisions in Accardi case show that it does not prohibit inquiry as to whether a decision which is required by law to be made was in fact made and I think the point is even sharpened more by the fact that now we have an affidavit.","start":529.263,"stop":546.388,"duration":17.13},{"text":"An affidavit from a man who has not been cross examined, an affidavit which we have not been permitted to impeach which purports through what is a disputed fact.","start":546.388,"stop":561.086,"duration":14.7}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"If this time the statement, these two statements and part of the original record, would you think that you could cross examine the former Secretary and the present Secretary on how they reached the conclusions and what their --","start":561.086,"stop":582.811,"duration":21.73}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that would present a much more difficult issue Your Honor, but I think we should be able to interrogate them particularly if they are not operating on the basis of a contemporaneous document.","start":582.811,"stop":597.257,"duration":14.45},{"text":"In other words, these are not documents that were written at the time the decision was made.","start":597.257,"stop":601.116,"duration":3.86},{"text":"These are, what I characterize as litigation affidavits.","start":601.116,"stop":604.12,"duration":3},{"text":"These are obviously prepared with the help of a lawyer, with the scope of lawsuit firmly in mind and filed in the court and I think it would not be an appropriate in circumstances of that nature to ask him, whether in fact he made the decisions and if so what materials he had before him.","start":604.12,"stop":621.394,"duration":17.27},{"text":"I don't think it would be proper, and may not be proper to say, did you read every page as they tried to do in Morgan or did you consider this factor on page one and that factor on page two.","start":621.394,"stop":631.238,"duration":9.84},{"text":"But I think it is fair, I think those attacking decisions must be able to ascertain what decisions were made and what the basis that is, what the documents before the person would have been in order that they can seek a review , in other words they can seek a review of what he did on the basis of what he purportedly acted upon.","start":631.238,"stop":652.466,"duration":21.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Supposing the appellant to the Chief Justice's question, supposing the secretary had made formal findings of that (Inaudible)","start":652.466,"stop":663.401,"duration":10.93}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that in order to cross examine in a case such as that, you'd have to make a strong showing that there had been some impropriety.","start":663.401,"stop":672.085,"duration":8.68},{"text":"There are cases, and I believe in Accardi case there was a finding or in the Singer Sewing Machine Case there were some findings where these quasi judicial body's members I don't remember, people associated with them were interrogated.","start":672.085,"stop":687.274,"duration":15.19},{"text":"But certainly there would be no reason if we had formal findings in this case, it would take a very strong showing in order to interrogate him and I'm not prepared to say, it would even being necessary, if we had the proper findings in this case.","start":687.274,"stop":702.833,"duration":15.56},{"text":"But the important fact is --","start":702.833,"stop":704.082,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Proper findings based on what?","start":704.082,"stop":707.48,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Proper findings -- of course, that would be a question as to whether or not they are based on evidence which supports them.","start":707.48,"stop":716.206,"duration":8.73},{"text":"Whether or not the Secretary has considered everything, he ought to have considered and whether or not, what he did consider supports what he did.","start":716.206,"stop":726.614,"duration":10.41},{"text":"I think it's not, there is no --","start":726.614,"stop":728.759,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) on the record though surely, wouldn't it, (Inaudible)","start":728.759,"stop":734.462,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that's correct.","start":734.462,"stop":735.339,"duration":0.88},{"text":"I think that's correct.","start":735.339,"stop":736.43,"duration":1.09},{"text":"It will determine, whether he made a proper investigation and brought before him the materials which he ought to brought before him for making such determination and whether these materials support his determination.","start":736.43,"stop":752.448,"duration":16.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You say, depend on the record, do you mean the record of evidence or something on which the findings were made?","start":752.448,"stop":758.686,"duration":6.24}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't mean any formal record.","start":758.686,"stop":760.755,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not talking about formal, could he just make a statement,without any hearing of evidence of any kind or character and would that close it out?","start":760.755,"stop":771.97,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe it would, Your Honor.","start":771.97,"stop":774.059,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"He testified to the administrator record, isn't that correct?","start":774.059,"stop":778.873,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is in this case, no specific administrator record.","start":778.873,"stop":782.581,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then (Inaudible) my brother Harlan's question.","start":782.581,"stop":785.43,"duration":2.85},{"text":"You have findings and an administrative record, you'd see, whether or not the findings were supported by the administrative record.","start":785.43,"stop":791.326,"duration":5.9},{"text":"That the test I know, of review is something that's in controversy in this case, but in any event that's the way you would approach it, isn't it?","start":791.326,"stop":801.315,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that we would be limited to the administrative record.","start":801.315,"stop":805.144,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Certainly, if we could show that, that his findings were not supported by what is characterized as the administrative work record, we would be entitled to relief, but I think that we should be able to show, we would also be entitled to relief if he didn't prepare a proper record, but further more if he has considered matters which those attacking his decision and not yet had an opportunity to rebut, I think that we would be entitled to rebut that evidence in someway and if we can cast some doubt on the credibility or the substantially of these findings based on evidence which we submitted, I think we will be entitled to relief --","start":805.144,"stop":844.046,"duration":38.9}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That answer suggests to me that you consider this adversary action an almost a full scale lawsuit between you and your group, your client on the one hand and the secretary on the other, is that the way you visualize this procedure?","start":844.046,"stop":858.765,"duration":14.72}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think we must be given a right to rebut evidence which we have not been appraised of on which he relied on, an evidence which we heretofore had not been --","start":858.765,"stop":867.517,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Why, why?","start":867.517,"stop":868.822,"duration":1.3},{"text":"What gives your client standing to become an adversary in a litigation between -- with the secretary under the statute?","start":868.822,"stop":879.157,"duration":10.34}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that the question of our standing is, I think at least not been opposed at this point.","start":879.157,"stop":886.265,"duration":7.11},{"text":"We do have standing, I believe under --","start":886.265,"stop":887.993,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the question is standing to do what?","start":887.993,"stop":890.007,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":890.007,"stop":892.002,"duration":2},{"text":"I think we have standing, we certainly have standing to present during the course of the administrative process at the public caring and elsewhere, we have standing to present evidence to --","start":892.002,"stop":902.472,"duration":10.47}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a public hearing in the Memphis City Council?","start":902.472,"stop":904.895,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and there were certain --","start":904.895,"stop":906.363,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And I suppose your people were heard from, were they not?","start":906.363,"stop":908.745,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They certainly were but now the secretary offers another, if I can give, Your Honor, one example, I think it will point out the necessity for this.","start":908.745,"stop":919.104,"duration":10.36},{"text":"They say we couldn't, apparently -- in document, they said in their affidavit, we couldn't like depressed route through this park, because this would require use of a particularly type of pump and this is unsafe in highway projects of this nature.","start":919.104,"stop":937.115,"duration":18.01},{"text":"Now if we are not permitted to rebut that in any way, we would not be able to show that the Department of Transportation has authorized for use in the interstate highway, the same type of pump in other areas and that cast such strong doubt as to either the investigation which he has made to the safety in this case, or as to creditability of this explanation, that it's evidence I submit, should is relevant for the consideration of the Trial Court.","start":937.115,"stop":969.051,"duration":31.94},{"text":"It may send it -- it maybe relevant only to whether or not he's made the proper investigation for making his determination, but it's evidence of that nature.","start":969.051,"stop":979.047,"duration":10},{"text":"In fact, there has been no objection heretofore on introducing such evidence.","start":979.047,"stop":983.036,"duration":3.99},{"text":"The Secretary has never objected of introduction of evidence of that nature.","start":983.036,"stop":986.461,"duration":3.43},{"text":"We have introduced affidavits which documented that the use of siphon in Department of Interior projects, we introduced affidavits of the use of this type of pump that would be required here, we have introduced affidavits as to the type of the use of tunnels in the interstate system.","start":986.461,"stop":1006.052,"duration":19.59},{"text":"They have not heretofore objected to that type of evidence.","start":1006.052,"stop":1010.252,"duration":4.2},{"text":"But it would only -- I don't think that this would not be a De novo advisory proceeding in which we tried out every fact.","start":1010.252,"stop":1018.022,"duration":7.77},{"text":"It would only be in case we are able to present some evidence which created some dispute over whether what the Secretary found on the basis of the administrative record.","start":1018.022,"stop":1030.083,"duration":12.06}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not quite sure Mr. Vardaman, in response to the questions and so I would like to try again on this matter of cross examination of the Secretary.","start":1030.083,"stop":1038.58,"duration":8.5},{"text":"If he had made the findings, and then said on the basis of these findings, I have concluded that this project is desirable and in conformance with the statutory requirements and it is hereby approved.","start":1038.58,"stop":1052.498,"duration":13.92},{"text":"In that circumstance with those formal findings, I don't quite understand whether you say you can examine -- cross examine him a little bit or not at all?","start":1052.498,"stop":1065.932,"duration":13.43}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I wouldn't say we can cross examine him a little bit.","start":1065.932,"stop":1069.518,"duration":3.59},{"text":"We would not, I say, be permitted to cross examine him unless we would meet the strong burden in the trial court that suggested some impropriety in what he did.","start":1069.518,"stop":1081.688,"duration":12.17},{"text":"For instance, and I don't mean to suggest that this would be true in this case or whatsoever, but as a hypothetical example, if there were some evidence to indicate fraud or bribery, it might be that type of attack on the findings I believe it would be proper and I think we could cross examine.","start":1081.688,"stop":1100.203,"duration":18.51},{"text":"In the Accardi case, there was an allegation that the Board of Immigration Appeals acted solely on the basis of the attorney general's list that had been published and there the court held, it was proper to cross examine.","start":1100.203,"stop":1113.49,"duration":13.29},{"text":"But only after we have met a very strong burden of demonstrating that there is some impropriety.","start":1113.49,"stop":1120.348,"duration":6.86},{"text":"I think it would shift the burden to us, it would place a very heavy burden upon us but in the general case, in the usual case, I would suggest that we would not cross examine in those circumstances, but in this particular case, where have this affidavit of Secretary, former Secretary Boyd, we do have evidence which will dispute this.","start":1120.348,"stop":1147.707,"duration":27.36},{"text":"I am not so concerned about cross examining Secretary Board as I am presenting that evidence.","start":1147.707,"stop":1152.491,"duration":4.78},{"text":"And it's interesting the reason it hasn't been presented heretofore is because former Highway Administrator Bridwell said he didn't think it was proper when I talked to him, to present this by affidavit.","start":1152.491,"stop":1162.516,"duration":10.03},{"text":"He thought it was better if he wouldn't take side, that we would testify in court and let both sides have a shot at him.","start":1162.516,"stop":1168.869,"duration":6.35},{"text":"We weren't permitted to put him on the stand to have him testify.","start":1168.869,"stop":1171.323,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think he is the appropriate person to make that decision?","start":1171.323,"stop":1175.09,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No I don't but I am simply explaining why we don't have an affidavit of the same nature that they do here today.","start":1175.09,"stop":1181.363,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does these affidavit -- are these statements here, late statement, show when a decision was made if a decision was made?","start":1181.363,"stop":1190.604,"duration":9.24}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the certificate of Allen Boyd says, in April of 1968, he made a decision that there was no feasible and prudent alternative routing the highway generally along in the --","start":1190.604,"stop":1204.381,"duration":13.78}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It was three years ago, has anything else shown except this evidence?","start":1204.381,"stop":1209.326,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not on this affidavit but --","start":1209.326,"stop":1211.616,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think in the record claims to show that they did have an investigation and did make a finding as to what route was feasible?","start":1211.616,"stop":1220.046,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well there are very vague allegations in an affidavit that in 1968, Secretary Boyd and former Federal Highway Administrator, Bridwell reaffirmed a previous decision and that's the extent of the documentation.","start":1220.046,"stop":1236.681,"duration":16.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"1960 -- 1968 affirmed and previously --","start":1236.681,"stop":1239.604,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1239.604,"stop":1240.729,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But when was the previous --","start":1240.729,"stop":1242.134,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They claimed it was made in 1956, but that other evidence in the record which --","start":1242.134,"stop":1247.587,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Anything in the record they have that shows except this affidavit three-five days ago?","start":1247.587,"stop":1253.556,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not that shows that these decisions were made, not that it says these decisions were made.","start":1253.556,"stop":1260.405,"duration":6.85},{"text":"In fact the record indicate, the affidavit of Volpe refers to another determination in 1969.","start":1260.405,"stop":1270.748,"duration":10.34},{"text":"The record is equally unclear on that point.","start":1270.748,"stop":1276.825,"duration":6.08},{"text":"Finally, the third point which we submit should be resolved by this Court before any remand which the Solicitor General, as I understand is conceded is necessary in this case, would be the appropriate standard of review.","start":1276.825,"stop":1291.41,"duration":14.59},{"text":"The Court of Appeals felt that the only standard of review is the arbitrary and capricious standard.","start":1291.41,"stop":1296.568,"duration":5.16},{"text":"The Administrative Procedure Act posses that is the minimum constitutional requirement.","start":1296.568,"stop":1302.694,"duration":6.13},{"text":"So the legislative history says and the act we believe requires a Court to go further and even if the finding is not arbitrary capricious, it requires a review of the evidence to support it.","start":1302.694,"stop":1314.693,"duration":12},{"text":"Either under the substantial evidence standard or the unwarranted by the fact standard, we believe that the court below was in error in limiting its review to the arbitrary and capricious standard","start":1314.693,"stop":1326.995,"duration":12.3}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Vardaman.","start":1326.995,"stop":1339.208,"duration":12.21},{"text":"I have Mr. Solicitor General --","start":1339.208,"stop":1346.08,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the same one that was here before and while it's coming, I will refer to the facts of the case to which Mr. Vardaman has not made much reference this morning.","start":1346.08,"stop":1362.601,"duration":16.52},{"text":"The park which is involved here, Overton Park in Memphis, is about 8 tenths of a mile across.","start":1362.601,"stop":1370.588,"duration":7.99},{"text":"One place in the record, it says 4800 feet, another place it seems to indicate it's 4100 feet and I take an intermediate place and call it 8 tenths of a mile.","start":1370.588,"stop":1381.705,"duration":11.12}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is from East to West Mr. Solicitor General?","start":1381.705,"stop":1383.259,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"From east to west.","start":1383.259,"stop":1384.136,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is the direction --","start":1384.136,"stop":1385.19,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is the direction that the highway comes.","start":1385.19,"stop":1389.663,"duration":4.47},{"text":"The record is clear that the location of the road through the park was approved by the Bureau of Public Roads in 1956, 15 years ago now.","start":1389.663,"stop":1401.739,"duration":12.08},{"text":"It is true as Mr. Vardaman says that at later times, there have been suggestion that it might be subject to reconsideration, but that would be like a petition for rehearing, that does not negative the fact that it was approved in 1956.","start":1401.739,"stop":1415.735,"duration":14},{"text":"It was reaffirmed by Federal Highway Administrator, Whitton in January 1966, five years ago and both of these were before there was any statutory provisions with respect to parks.","start":1415.735,"stop":1432.424,"duration":16.69},{"text":"Section 4 (f) of the Department of Transportation Act was enacted in October 1966 and effective April 1, 1967.","start":1432.424,"stop":1444.391,"duration":11.97},{"text":"The approval of the route was reconfirmed by the Department of the Transportation Secretary, Boyd on April 1968.","start":1444.391,"stop":1456.057,"duration":11.67},{"text":"The Section 4 (f) was amended and Section 138 of the Federal Aid Highway Act was enacted and effective in August 1968 and the design, only the design, because Secretary Volpe gave no consideration to the location, that had been determined in 1956, 1966 and reconfirmed by Secretary Boyd in 1968, the design was approved by Secretary Volpe on November 5, 1969.","start":1456.057,"stop":1492.618,"duration":36.56},{"text":"I would like to recall the fact that the statute provides that and I quote, “To the greatest extend possible” the state shall select the route for highways and this route has been approved by the state, the city and by the Memphis Park Board.","start":1492.618,"stop":1513.07,"duration":20.45},{"text":"The Tennessee highway department was authorized to proceed with the purchase of the right-of-way on May 29, 1967 nearly four years ago, and commenced doing so, and the area is not immediately adjacent to the park.","start":1513.07,"stop":1531.189,"duration":18.12},{"text":"At the present time and this is true with one or two exceptions that at the time the suit was started, all of the land has been acquired to and through the park.","start":1531.189,"stop":1542.05,"duration":10.86},{"text":"99% of the nearly 2,000 people living their had been displaced and 75% of the buildings had been demolished.","start":1542.05,"stop":1552.477,"duration":10.43},{"text":"Some of the land has been (Inaudible) Now the red line East to West is the approved route of the park.","start":1552.477,"stop":1564.768,"duration":12.29},{"text":"That which has the green dash lines beside it is land where the right-of-way was cleared prior to April 1968, the date of Secretary Boyd's approval.","start":1564.768,"stop":1580.796,"duration":16.03},{"text":"All of this was cleared by August 1966, before the effective date of either the statutes involved here.","start":1580.796,"stop":1591.908,"duration":11.11},{"text":"The land with a yellow along the red is land which was cleared after April 1968, after the date of Secretary Boyd's approval.","start":1591.908,"stop":1604.287,"duration":12.38}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that in the park?","start":1604.287,"stop":1608.633,"duration":4.35},{"text":"That land you refer to was that in the park?","start":1608.633,"stop":1610.374,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the park is this area Mr. Justice from there to there, and that is all that we are concerned with here.","start":1610.374,"stop":1619.641,"duration":9.27},{"text":"What I am trying to point out is that the land up to the park on both sides was cleared after April 1968, and substantially all cleared by January 1969 when Secretary Volpe took office, and all cleared by November 1969, when he approved the design.","start":1619.641,"stop":1642.526,"duration":22.88},{"text":"Now here it is, one of the alternate which was considered, here is another alternate that was considered, this triangular line is an alternate which is suggested in one of the affidavits that's filed by the petitioners in this case.","start":1642.526,"stop":1664.32,"duration":21.79},{"text":"This is a pedestrian bridge for access to the zoo.","start":1664.32,"stop":1669.035,"duration":4.72},{"text":"This also is a pedestrian bridge with access to the zoo, and this is a cross street, which is left open.","start":1669.035,"stop":1679.792,"duration":10.76},{"text":"The state has bought the 26 acres through the park, for $2,200,000, and the city has already expended $1,000,000 for 160 acre park with a golf course, and it spent $200,000 on improvements to the zoo, and is obligated to expend the remaining million dollars for additional parkland.","start":1679.792,"stop":1708.485,"duration":28.69},{"text":"And thus the park resources of Memphis will be increased by some 320 acres on account of the loss of 26 acres in Overton Park.","start":1708.485,"stop":1719.424,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course acreage is more important but even more important in parks, with respect to parks is their locations, one of the few things perhaps I learned as a member of the city council of Cincinnati that where the parks are is of the greatest importance?","start":1719.424,"stop":1738.627,"duration":19.2}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand Mr. Justice, and I am little bit inhibited because there is nothing in the record about where the parks are.","start":1738.627,"stop":1744.99,"duration":6.36},{"text":"I had made inquiries and as far as I am concerned, the park has substantial improvement to the park facilities of Memphis in terms of location as well as area.","start":1744.99,"stop":1756.573,"duration":11.58},{"text":"But I can't --","start":1756.573,"stop":1756.924,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Accessibility to the people who need the park --","start":1756.924,"stop":1760.505,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I am so advised and perhaps and Mr. Hanover can tell you more about that.","start":1760.505,"stop":1766.195,"duration":5.69},{"text":"The location of the new park does not appeared in the record.","start":1766.195,"stop":1772.643,"duration":6.45},{"text":"Our brief answers the arguments made by the petitioners and I believe that we have an argument and answer to each argument.","start":1772.643,"stop":1780.929,"duration":8.29},{"text":"We rely on that brief.","start":1780.929,"stop":1783.583,"duration":2.65},{"text":"In the brief time available to me for oral argument, I cannot deal with all of the arguments here, but I will confine my consideration to four points.","start":1783.583,"stop":1795.043,"duration":11.46},{"text":"There are special circumstances here, which makes this a suitable place to put this role and which support the determination of the Secretary that there is no other 'feasible and prudent' and I emphasis the fact that the statute says 'and prudent' alternative to this route. Overton Park has always been divided.","start":1795.043,"stop":1818.358,"duration":23.32},{"text":"There is in fact the park and the zoo, and for 75 years or so they have been separated.","start":1818.358,"stop":1827.226,"duration":8.87},{"text":"This is the zoo.","start":1827.226,"stop":1829.57,"duration":2.34},{"text":"The zoo has been extended into this area and this although it appears to be trees, is trees has parking space under it.","start":1829.57,"stop":1837.439,"duration":7.87},{"text":"The park is south of the road.","start":1837.439,"stop":1841.099,"duration":3.66},{"text":"At first there was a narrow gauge railway across the land at this point, then trolley tracks, and for the past 30 years or so the trolley tracks have been replaced by a paved bus route.","start":1841.099,"stop":1853.559,"duration":12.46},{"text":"This right-of-way is 40 or 50 feet wide and it has city bus traffic with no protection, and that is been there for 60 or 70 years in one form or another.","start":1853.559,"stop":1867.652,"duration":14.09},{"text":"There is however and always has been limited access to the zoo, and that's what they want.","start":1867.652,"stop":1874.379,"duration":6.73},{"text":"Along the bus route at the South side of the zoo there is a chain link fence 6 or 7 feet high, except at the East end where the parking lot for the zoo is located and will continue to be located.","start":1874.379,"stop":1888.248,"duration":13.87},{"text":"The bus route already occupies 4 or 5 acres which of course has no trees on it.","start":1888.248,"stop":1894.769,"duration":6.52},{"text":"So we are talking about 21 or 22 acres.","start":1894.769,"stop":1898.491,"duration":3.72},{"text":"The park now contains 150 acres of unimproved woodland.","start":1898.491,"stop":1903.425,"duration":4.93},{"text":"It can be seen here at the lake so that the statement made in one of the letters in the record and relied on in the petitioners' brief that there won't be much in the way of wooded park left in Overton Park after an interstate highway is routed through it is obviously a greatly over exaggerated statement.","start":1903.425,"stop":1924.864,"duration":21.44},{"text":"There will be at least 130 acres of wooded parkland left in Overton Park.","start":1924.864,"stop":1931.967,"duration":7.1}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What's a climax forest, do you have any idea?","start":1931.967,"stop":1936.091,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No Mr. Justice I have some recollection that I read about it once many years ago, but I can't tell you --","start":1936.091,"stop":1941.403,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I heard about it in the petitioners' brief and I perhaps will look it up in the dictionary but I just wondered if you knew about it?","start":1941.403,"stop":1947.09,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps the petitioners enlighten you.","start":1947.09,"stop":1949.24,"duration":2.15},{"text":"I should have looked into it.","start":1949.24,"stop":1950.787,"duration":1.55},{"text":"It is a tree term, but I don't know it.","start":1950.787,"stop":1960.206,"duration":9.42},{"text":"With respect to the design much of the highways to be depressed so as to minimize the noise and interference with view.","start":1960.206,"stop":1968.064,"duration":7.86},{"text":"Secretary Volpe took great pains with respect to that.","start":1968.064,"stop":1971.921,"duration":3.86},{"text":"The place for the highway will be above grade to enable it to cross on (Inaudible), where engineering difficulty would be considerable and continuing, if the highway were depressed.","start":1971.921,"stop":1991.246,"duration":19.33},{"text":"The statute doesn't say, no other possible alternative.","start":1991.246,"stop":1996.154,"duration":4.91},{"text":"It does not even say no other feasible alternative.","start":1996.154,"stop":2000.656,"duration":4.5},{"text":"What it says is no other 'feasible and prudent' alternative in the conjunctive.","start":2000.656,"stop":2007.181,"duration":6.53},{"text":"There must be no other route that is prudent as well as feasible.","start":2007.181,"stop":2012.395,"duration":5.21},{"text":"According to my dictionary, prudent means wise in handling practical matters, exercising good judgment or common sense.","start":2012.395,"stop":2022.334,"duration":9.94},{"text":"The legislative history shows that it was intended that the Secretary should make this judgment.","start":2022.334,"stop":2028.232,"duration":5.9},{"text":"We submit that it is cleared on this record that both Secretaries had adequate support for their conclusion.","start":2028.232,"stop":2035.43,"duration":7.2},{"text":"That there is no feasible and prudent alternative to the use of this land and that all possible planing to minimize harm to the park has been done.","start":2035.43,"stop":2048.143,"duration":12.71},{"text":"Now I turn to the question of findings.","start":2048.143,"stop":2051.882,"duration":3.74},{"text":"The statute doesn't require findings or a trial-type hearing by the Secretary, and it would be a mistake for this Court to conclude we respectfully submit that findings by the Secretary are required or that he should be required to conduct a trail-type hearing.","start":2051.882,"stop":2073.489,"duration":21.61},{"text":"Following a suggestion which was made in the previous oral argument in this case, we have obtained from both Secretaries involved certificates, stating their findings.","start":2073.489,"stop":2085.016,"duration":11.53},{"text":"Now these are referred to by Mr. Vardaman, understandably as affidavits, but they are not so denominated themselves.","start":2085.016,"stop":2094.145,"duration":9.13},{"text":"They are certificates made by a high government officer with respect to actions which they took and they do we submit serve to clarify any ambiguity which may lie in the record by reason of the fact that they did not make formal findings, which I again submit the statute does not require them to do.","start":2094.145,"stop":2116.214,"duration":22.07},{"text":"We recognize that the presentation of these documents is unusual.","start":2116.214,"stop":2121.67,"duration":5.46},{"text":"We submit them for what effect they can properly be given.","start":2121.67,"stop":2126.17,"duration":4.5},{"text":"I repeat the suggestion came from the previous oral argument in the Court.","start":2126.17,"stop":2134.783,"duration":8.61},{"text":"We had them nicely printed up, but Secretary Volpe has been out of town.","start":2134.783,"stop":2140.211,"duration":5.43},{"text":"His affidavit was cleared with him by telephone.","start":2140.211,"stop":2143.667,"duration":3.46},{"text":"It was to be signed this morning and when he came to sign it, he wanted to change and of course, it's his certificate and so he changed it, and the result is that we have withdrawn the printed copies which we had prepared in advance and have submitted the original of the certificates to the Court and had provided the xerox copies to counsel and to the Court.","start":2143.667,"stop":2169.373,"duration":25.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Solicitor General, may I ask you in view of your statement, there is no formal findings a requirement. What kind, would you say -- what do you thought to take care of the precautionary action which the Congress has prescribed?","start":2169.373,"stop":2187.135,"duration":17.76}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, Mr. Justice.","start":2187.135,"stop":2188.163,"duration":1.03},{"text":"I think that it should appear in some appropriate way and I hope that these certificates are shall I say, last resort appropriate way.","start":2188.163,"stop":2198.341,"duration":10.18},{"text":"That the Secretaries did, in fact, recognize and take into account and undertake to operate under the statutory requirement, clearly and validly made by Congress.","start":2198.341,"stop":2213.394,"duration":15.05},{"text":"We think that even without these formal certificates from the Secretaries, there is sufficient in the record to show that they did proceed on that basis.","start":2213.394,"stop":2222.321,"duration":8.93},{"text":"But what the statute says is that the Secretary shall not approve any program or project involving park lands unless one, there is no feasible and prudent alternative to the use of such land and two such program includes all possible planning to minimize harm to such part resulting from such use.","start":2222.321,"stop":2243.67,"duration":21.35},{"text":"It does not even say, unless the Secretary finds that there is no such alternative and I suspect that, that was because Congress deliberately wanted to avoid the Secretary having to hold hearing and take evidence and balance the evidence and then in the way, that a Court does after a trial type hearing make a finding of fact.","start":2243.67,"stop":2264.866,"duration":21.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything in the congressional hearings or record to support that?","start":2264.866,"stop":2270.672,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice, the legislative history is detailed both in the appendix to petitioner's brief and in our brief.","start":2270.672,"stop":2287.95,"duration":17.28},{"text":"Particularly, on page 21 there are statements of our brief.","start":2287.95,"stop":2292.609,"duration":4.66},{"text":"There are statements in the report of the Senate Public Works Committee and in the report of the House Committee on Public Works.","start":2292.609,"stop":2302.723,"duration":10.11},{"text":"Committee is extremely concerned that the highway program be carried out in such a manner as to reduce in all instances, the harsh impact on people which results from the dislocation and displacement by reason of highway construction.","start":2302.723,"stop":2316.657,"duration":13.93},{"text":"Therefore, the use of park lands properly protect it and with the damage minimized by the most sophisticated construction techniques is to be preferred to the movement of large numbers of people.","start":2316.657,"stop":2328.694,"duration":12.04},{"text":"There is a colloquy in the Senate to which reference is made in the appendix to the petitioner's brief, which he seems to say, at least, to the conclusion that the Secretary has no discretion but which we read in exactly the opposite way.","start":2328.694,"stop":2345.929,"duration":17.24},{"text":"We read it to say that if the local people say that these parks can't be used, then the Secretary has no discretion, but that if they say they can be used, it still remains a matter for the Secretary's judgment as to whether there is a feasible and prudent alternative.","start":2345.929,"stop":2363.582,"duration":17.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I right in thinking that your current departmental regulations do provide it?","start":2363.582,"stop":2368.466,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice, the department is upgrading the procedures here and I think that's sound, but I know off no reason why that should be applied retroactively to proceedings which were already filed along by the time that was adopted and I don't read the Thorpe case on which the petitioners rely as leading to any such conclusion.","start":2368.466,"stop":2397.1,"duration":28.63},{"text":"The question here is whether -- it is clear here that here that both Secretaries understood the requirement of the statute and they've now both certified, but they did understand it and that they complied with it.","start":2397.1,"stop":2411.786,"duration":14.69},{"text":"Now this Court has often held that formal finding should not be insisted on, when they're not legislatively commanded.","start":2411.786,"stop":2420.671,"duration":8.88},{"text":"The standard of review should be whether the actions of the Secretaries was arbitrary and capricious.","start":2420.671,"stop":2427.389,"duration":6.72},{"text":"We think that the petitioners are far from having sustained their burden of proof, that there was such arbitrary and capricious action here.","start":2427.389,"stop":2436.506,"duration":9.12},{"text":"We think that his record contains ample material that shows that both Secretaries acted carefully, thoughtfully, deliberately and was full awareness of their obligation under the statute, but it was their decision and they made it.","start":2436.506,"stop":2451.746,"duration":15.24},{"text":"The task was one of great responsibility and they should be upheld.","start":2451.746,"stop":2457.696,"duration":5.95},{"text":"The Administrative Procedure Act does not apply to this, because it's a grant making matter which is especially excluded from the Act, but if it does reply, it would lead to the same result.","start":2457.696,"stop":2471.259,"duration":13.56},{"text":"But if the Court feels that the question--","start":2471.259,"stop":2472.838,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask Mr. Solicitor, my recollection is (Inaudible)","start":2472.838,"stop":2485.754,"duration":12.92}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice, I'm just turning to that.","start":2485.754,"stop":2488.868,"duration":3.11},{"text":"If the Court feels that the question of arbitrary and capricious action cannot be determined on this record, and we felt there was some indication of that in the previous argument then we rely on our motion to remand for the purpose of allowing the admission of the administrative record in the District Court.","start":2488.868,"stop":2507.362,"duration":18.49},{"text":"We do not think that there should be a remand for a full trial, unless the District Court finds after examining the administrative record, that it cannot decided the issue of arbitrary and capricious action without a further a trial.","start":2507.362,"stop":2523.852,"duration":16.49},{"text":"We filed the motion of remand not for the purpose of conceding error here as Mr. Vardaman says, but for the purpose of narrowing the scope of any remand, and for the purpose of negativing any suggestion, that there should not be such a limited remand because we have not asked for such a limitation.","start":2523.852,"stop":2546.008,"duration":22.16},{"text":"Now the -- I see that my time is virtually expired.","start":2546.008,"stop":2550.942,"duration":4.93},{"text":"I will have to summarize my remaining points.","start":2550.942,"stop":2555.014,"duration":4.07},{"text":"The third one I wanted to make was that a remand here, would it seems to me be a triumph for formalism.","start":2555.014,"stop":2563.354,"duration":8.34},{"text":"With the benefit for hindsight this record is not all that I might like to have.","start":2563.354,"stop":2568.659,"duration":5.31},{"text":"It would be nicer, if the Secretaries had made formal findings at the time they made their determinations, though they have made such a findings nows.","start":2568.659,"stop":2577.846,"duration":9.19},{"text":"It would be better, if we didn't have to piece out the essence of their determinations from other actions which they took like press releases and resolutions and letters and affidavits.","start":2577.846,"stop":2590.347,"duration":12.5},{"text":"And it was for this reason, that we moved for the introduction of the remand, or the introduction of the administrative record, but is this not really an exercise in futility.","start":2590.347,"stop":2602.59,"duration":12.24},{"text":"Would it not be a triumph of formalism over substance or Mr. Justice Frankfurter in it's well known words, a case of marching the king's men up the hill and then marching them down again.","start":2602.59,"stop":2615.789,"duration":13.2},{"text":"And remand for further proceedings, would I think be a kind of mechanical jurisprudence more of fitting for barren park than for the final third the 20th Century.","start":2615.789,"stop":2626.97,"duration":11.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't quite understand that Mr. Solicitor?","start":2626.97,"stop":2630.162,"duration":3.19},{"text":"Congress has passed an Act which seems to attach great importance for not not going to trial (Inaudible) feasible and prudent (Inaudible)","start":2630.162,"stop":2650.927,"duration":20.77}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, my point is that I think that there is ample and adequate in the record now to make it plain, that if this is remanded, it will great deal of motion will be generated and when you get through the motion, there will then be a nice new record which will have adequate material to show that the route is not -- there is no feasible and prudent --","start":2650.927,"stop":2671.872,"duration":20.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) record which does not now appear?","start":2671.872,"stop":2676.014,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, we think that there isn't.","start":2676.014,"stop":2678.819,"duration":2.8},{"text":"If this test of review is whether the Secretary acted in an arbitrary and capricious manner which we think is the test, we think it is a apparent from this record that neither Secretary acted in an arbitrary or capricious manner, ignoring their requirements of the statue.","start":2678.819,"stop":2696.122,"duration":17.3},{"text":"If that does not adequately appear, then we think the case should be remanded so that the administrative record can be seen by the District Court and that question determined on the administrative record.","start":2696.122,"stop":2708.761,"duration":12.64},{"text":"What we think should not be done here, is anything which requires a trail type hearing before the Secretary or anything which leads to, what amounts to a trial de novo before a district court and a decision of this question in effect by the District Court rather than by the Secretary.","start":2708.761,"stop":2727.87,"duration":19.11},{"text":"Because that is my final point, a fundamental question here, one of the separation powers, of the proper allocation of the function that courts, legislatures and the executive branch in the important and complex task of carrying on government.","start":2727.87,"stop":2744.903,"duration":17.03},{"text":"Two things are clear, one is that Congress is legislated certain specific requirements with respect to the use of park lands and the other is that it is allocated the administration of that provision to the executive branch specifically to the Secretary of Transportation.","start":2744.903,"stop":2763.436,"duration":18.53},{"text":"This doesn't mean that there is no role for the courts where the Secretary should be held and check if he ignores the legislative requirements.","start":2763.436,"stop":2772.448,"duration":9.01},{"text":"But it does mean that the proper role of the courts is now unlimited one and it is important I submit, both through the administration of the government and for the courts, that the limited nature of that role be recognized and observed.","start":2772.448,"stop":2788.906,"duration":16.46},{"text":"It is not good government to have all governmental decisions decided by courts or even that have a situation where as a matter of routine, all questions arising in the administration of the government are habitually referred to courts.","start":2788.906,"stop":2805.211,"duration":16.3},{"text":"In recent years, more and more governmental decisions are being made by courts.","start":2805.211,"stop":2810.691,"duration":5.48},{"text":"The recent broadening or near elimination of concepts of standing and the limitations on sovereign immunity as a defense have contributed to this result.","start":2810.691,"stop":2823.477,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Of course, court should see that the constitution is complied with and that the statutory rules are followed, but is it wise that the substance of all administrative actions should be subject to reevaluation in the courts.","start":2823.477,"stop":2839.904,"duration":16.43},{"text":"What the two secretaries have done here, they have acted, what they have done is rational, and it complies that is directives given to them by Congress.","start":2839.904,"stop":2849.9,"duration":10},{"text":"The decision was to remand, it should be upheld.","start":2849.9,"stop":2854.327,"duration":4.43},{"text":"The judgment below should be affirmed.","start":2854.327,"stop":2857.159,"duration":2.83},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, I'm afraid I have trespassed some on Mr. Hanover's time and I hope that he can have some of his time.","start":2857.159,"stop":2864.961,"duration":7.8}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll work it out reasonably Mr. Solicitor General.","start":2864.961,"stop":2868.554,"duration":3.59},{"text":"Mr. Hanover you may proceed.","start":2868.554,"stop":2870.641,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":2870.641,"stop":2876.547,"duration":5.91},{"text":"I will not at this time attempt to restate the facts or using time for that purpose, since I think that the Solicitor General has stated them quite well to the Court.","start":2876.547,"stop":2889.269,"duration":12.72},{"text":"I've being the only attorney at the bar today who has played in this park.","start":2889.269,"stop":2893.943,"duration":4.67},{"text":"I do feel that I probably know more the details than either of my colleagues.","start":2893.943,"stop":2901.848,"duration":7.9},{"text":"I would be of course happy to answer questions in that vein but I will pass from the facts to take up what I feel are the issues that affects this case, and affect my client, the State of Tennessee.","start":2901.848,"stop":2917.478,"duration":15.63},{"text":"I think the best place to start any argument is at the beginning and I think it would be helpful to the Court, if I went back to the beginning of this case, as it will help you to understand all five issues in this case.","start":2917.478,"stop":2938.504,"duration":21.03},{"text":"And the beginning of this case is the beginning of any case is the pleadings and the complaint filed by the petitioners in this case sets up the case, it sets up the standard of judicial review and it sets up what type of judicial review should be had in this case.","start":2938.504,"stop":2960.032,"duration":21.53},{"text":"In the petitioners' original complaint, they charge that the Secretary didn't make findings, that is really the only basic issue in the lawsuit.","start":2960.032,"stop":2974.319,"duration":14.29},{"text":"Actually, although, I was glad to see this morning the affidavits are filed by the Solicitor General and of course, the other affidavits in the record as to approval of the route and reaffirmation actually on the motion for summary judgment that was before the District Court and the Court of Appeals and is before this Court, None of those affidavits were actually necessary.","start":2974.319,"stop":2996.839,"duration":22.52},{"text":"The complaint filed by Mr. Vardaman states all of the necessary facts for this determination.","start":2996.839,"stop":3004.087,"duration":7.25},{"text":"He states that Secretary Boyd approved the route and of course, the word approved is the keyword in the statute.","start":3004.087,"stop":3012.461,"duration":8.37},{"text":"There is no dispute concerning the approval.","start":3012.461,"stop":3015.252,"duration":2.79},{"text":"There is no dispute concerning the final approval of the route design in November 1969.","start":3015.252,"stop":3023.205,"duration":7.95},{"text":"Since the complaint filed by the petitioner states all of those facts, and therefore they admit it.","start":3023.205,"stop":3030.605,"duration":7.4},{"text":"He raises the issue as to whether or not findings as such were required under the parkland statute and in the record, in the appendix, you'll see as cited in our brief, the colloquy that it occurred between Mr. Vardaman and District Judge Brown on this very point, as to what the issues were and what he was contending.","start":3030.605,"stop":3054.216,"duration":23.61},{"text":"I think it's quite clear that the issue was whether or not specific findings are necessary under the Act and that is, of course, I think the main problem that this Court has to face.","start":3054.216,"stop":3067.72,"duration":13.5},{"text":"If this Court believes as I do, and as the Solicitor General does that this is a discretionary statute that Congress gave the Secretary of Transportation, a discretion to make this decision and that findings as such or not require by the statute or by either the application or non-application of the Administrative Procedure Act.","start":3067.72,"stop":3090.863,"duration":23.14},{"text":"I feel I have discuss quite fully in our brief that it does not apply to discretionary decision of this type, that the Court can reach its conclusion and end this case one way or the other on that point alone.","start":3090.863,"stop":3104.891,"duration":14.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean by discretionary?","start":3104.891,"stop":3108.028,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"As contrasted Mr. Justice Black to a ministerial duty.","start":3108.028,"stop":3112.23,"duration":4.2},{"text":"He has to exercise judge, he has to exercise his judgment rather than the judgment of Mr. Vardaman or the Solicitor General or myself or any of the protagonist in this case.","start":3112.23,"stop":3124.941,"duration":12.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean a non-renewable?","start":3124.941,"stop":3126.715,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3126.715,"stop":3127.466,"duration":0.75},{"text":"I will take that point right now.","start":3127.466,"stop":3131.638,"duration":4.17},{"text":"I tend to agree to a certain extent with the Solicitor General, although we do disagree on one or two other points in this case, regarding administrative record, that the Administrative Procedure Act does not apply, but it really doesn't make any difference whether it does or not, the result in the case is the same.","start":3131.638,"stop":3150.41,"duration":18.77},{"text":"Now the question of review, as I stated earlier the complaint filed about Mr. Vardaman does not charge Secretary Volpe with any misconduct.","start":3150.41,"stop":3162.197,"duration":11.79},{"text":"It's always been my understanding of the law that when you challenge the actions of an administrator and you want to have a review on the question of whether he was arbitrary or capricious, you must allege some fact to bring it before the Court to have a trial on the merits which is what Mr. Vardaman ultimately wants.","start":3162.197,"stop":3182.618,"duration":20.42},{"text":"They didn't say, as a matter of fact, they didn't even make a conclusory allegation that Secretary Volpe was arbitrary and capricious.","start":3182.618,"stop":3190.829,"duration":8.21},{"text":"They just said he didn't make any findings.","start":3190.829,"stop":3192.962,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Now this Court holds the findings he must make, that's the end of that issue.","start":3192.962,"stop":3198.373,"duration":5.41},{"text":"If the Court holds that findings he need not make, that again is a dispositive to the issue.","start":3198.373,"stop":3204.696,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Now it's not that he is precluded from judicial review or this Court is precluded from reviewing case.","start":3204.696,"stop":3212.238,"duration":7.54},{"text":"It's because he did not allege facts that warrant judicial review beyond what he has here today.","start":3212.238,"stop":3220.05,"duration":7.81},{"text":"If he had said that Secretary Volpe laid this route out because he had a relative nearby who'd profit from the sale of his land or the enhancement of its value or that he deliberately refused to consider evidence or that he deliberately chose engineers to advise him and whom he knew were not properly trained, that maybe the basis for a review beyond the sculpt that we have here on the question of summary judgment, but he did not.","start":3220.05,"stop":3253.016,"duration":32.97},{"text":"He just simply said, he made no findings although he admittedly admits that he approved the route.","start":3253.016,"stop":3260.503,"duration":7.49},{"text":"Now going from that, there are many cases that have been before this Court and the lower Federal Courts to the effect that with those allegations, you can go farther and you can question the Secretary.","start":3260.503,"stop":3276.133,"duration":15.63},{"text":"I would think that if he had charged Secretary Volpe with some improper conduct, he would have a prefect right to examine him on that point.","start":3276.133,"stop":3290.488,"duration":14.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why did he fall short of it?","start":3290.488,"stop":3292.519,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"He just didn't allege any --","start":3292.519,"stop":3293.631,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What did he allege?","start":3293.631,"stop":3294.712,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"He only alleged, may it please Your Honor, that these various routes have been approved, the designs have been approved and that the Secretary has failed to make findings.","start":3294.712,"stop":3306.208,"duration":11.5},{"text":"Now, we've quoted that extensively in our brief to call it to the attention of the Court.","start":3306.208,"stop":3311.848,"duration":5.64},{"text":"I see that my time has expired.","start":3311.848,"stop":3316.118,"duration":4.27},{"text":"In conclusion I again ask the Court to, before determining the standard of judicial review or the question of whether the Secretary or Federal Administrator Bridwell should have been opposed, to carefully examine the pleadings to determine what the issues are.","start":3316.118,"stop":3331.537,"duration":15.42},{"text":"I think all of the other issues fall into place, after you see what the petitioners are actually claiming in this case.","start":3331.537,"stop":3340.997,"duration":9.46}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Hanover.","start":3340.997,"stop":3342.142,"duration":1.14},{"text":"Mr. Vardaman.","start":3342.142,"stop":3343.699,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, the respondents in this case traditionally start each argument with the statement that this highway will run along a bus route through the park, and the implication being we'll have practically no effect on this.","start":3343.699,"stop":3359.972,"duration":16.27},{"text":"This bus route which is displayed here is narrow facility, some 25 feet wide, on which buses run through about once in an hour, in fact it's so narrow that the trees from the wooded part of the park hang over the bus route freely crossed by pedestrians.","start":3359.972,"stop":3377.609,"duration":17.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Will it be for passengers only?","start":3377.609,"stop":3381.867,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The bus route is only used for about one bus an hour, no cars, no other traffic.","start":3381.867,"stop":3386.554,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the road to be used for passengers only, or from passengers and freighters?","start":3386.554,"stop":3391.518,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And trucks that interstate -- for commercial and passenger vehicles.","start":3391.518,"stop":3395.222,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Freight?","start":3395.222,"stop":3395.868,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Freight, trucks.","start":3395.868,"stop":3398.948,"duration":3.08},{"text":"The statements which they claim is unwarranted.","start":3398.948,"stop":3401.744,"duration":2.8},{"text":"The statement would says there won't be much of a wooded area left in the park, that's not a statement we made.","start":3401.744,"stop":3408.072,"duration":6.33},{"text":"That's a statement that an official of Department of Interior made, a department which the Secretary is statue found to consult with on projects of this nature.","start":3408.072,"stop":3417.552,"duration":9.48},{"text":"It is a document, fully part of the administrative record.","start":3417.552,"stop":3421.088,"duration":3.54},{"text":"They don't seek to dispute that.","start":3421.088,"stop":3423.733,"duration":2.64},{"text":"They within any other evidence they simply say it can't be right.","start":3423.733,"stop":3427.872,"duration":4.14},{"text":"We submit that Department of Interior --","start":3427.872,"stop":3429.724,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) is relevant or not but looking at the map from where I'm sitting, it could not conceivably be right?","start":3429.724,"stop":3436.768,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But I think what the official had in mind, not that a major part of the woodland would be taken.","start":3436.768,"stop":3443.945,"duration":7.18},{"text":"There will be a 450 foot right-of-way through that area.","start":3443.945,"stop":3447.285,"duration":3.34},{"text":"But what he meant was, not only that you take the 450 feet, but you really destroy the rest of the park because immediately you don't have a woodland park, immediately adjacent to the highway, if you got a six lane interstate highway going.","start":3447.285,"stop":3461.434,"duration":14.15},{"text":"You have beside the sound, the general pollution associate with these highways, which spread further than the right-of-way.","start":3461.434,"stop":3469.492,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How wide would you say it would be?","start":3469.492,"stop":3471.297,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"450 feet in the wooded area of the park, and I think anyone who has ever stood anywhere close to an interstate highway of this nature knows that the effects don't stops at the age of the pavement and I think Your Honor that's what the department of Interior official --","start":3471.297,"stop":3489.106,"duration":17.81}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The 400 -- the outer edge of the 450 feet are not paved?","start":3489.106,"stop":3493.148,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is very I -- it's not clear but I think --","start":3493.148,"stop":3497.201,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It really hasn't got much to do with the case, but I think you find that the 450 feet of the entire right-of-way doesn't extent nearly to the edge?","start":3497.201,"stop":3507.266,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But this was showed as I think in the case are very narrow.","start":3507.266,"stop":3511.772,"duration":4.51},{"text":"That's one of the points I made also that they didn't take very much.","start":3511.772,"stop":3515.67,"duration":3.9},{"text":"A second point which they raise is that the right-of-way for this route was acquired long before the decision -- was acquired after the decisions were made.","start":3515.67,"stop":3526.707,"duration":11.04},{"text":"In fact, the department of transportation authorized the acquisitions for the right-of-way of this project before they ever made any effort to comply with the statute.","start":3526.707,"stop":3537.611,"duration":10.9},{"text":"Even if we assume, what the Solicitor General says is correct, and even if we assume what is stated in these certificates are right, the department of transportation told the state to go ahead and acquire the land for this project in May 1967, a month after the statue was affected, but 11 months before any effort was made to comply with it.","start":3537.611,"stop":3559.07,"duration":21.46},{"text":"And I submit that right-of-way acquired under that authorization is acquired illegally which should not prejudice the petitioners' position.","start":3559.07,"stop":3569.799,"duration":10.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Review under the case briefly what is exactly that you expect to be able to show if this case is remanded?","start":3569.799,"stop":3579.224,"duration":9.43}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll be able to show Your Honor, that in my test, my evidence would show that the officials of the department of transportation left this decision solely to the City Council of Memphis.","start":3579.224,"stop":3593.672,"duration":14.45},{"text":"They went down and made an explanation, and they although they pointed out alternatives both to the North and to the South of the park, they never decided one way or the other in the Department of Transportation, that these alternatives, whether these alternatives were prudent and feasible.","start":3593.672,"stop":3608.686,"duration":15.01},{"text":"They attempted to delegate to the City Council, and once a City Council made up its mind, they simply rubber stamped that.","start":3608.686,"stop":3616.526,"duration":7.84},{"text":"They approved the highway without ever making their own independent judgment as to whether they were feasible and prudent alternatives.","start":3616.526,"stop":3625.896,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you going to do that without cross-examining Mr. Boyd and Mr. Volpe?","start":3625.896,"stop":3629.913,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what Mr. Bridwell would testified to.","start":3629.913,"stop":3634.091,"duration":4.18},{"text":"I think it's also supported by the evidence, his testimony before the Congress which is in exhibit in this case, but that's what Secretary Bridwell would testify to.","start":3634.091,"stop":3646.601,"duration":12.51},{"text":"And I think that even in footnote 25 of the Solicitor General's brief, he concedes that the statute imposes an obligation on the Secretary of Transportation, to make an independent determination, and we will show that independent determination was never made in this case.","start":3646.601,"stop":3663.315,"duration":16.71}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) as a practical question (Inaudible) the certificates (Inaudible)","start":3663.315,"stop":3671.617,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":3671.617,"stop":3672.619,"duration":1},{"text":"I say, we have evidence which would dispute --","start":3672.619,"stop":3675.359,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather you claim that they not only did not make the so called formal findings, but they made no findings at all?","start":3675.359,"stop":3683.801,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, didn't even make a minimal determination.","start":3683.801,"stop":3687.488,"duration":3.69},{"text":"Further with respect to the design, we would show that designs which they reject as impossible are in fact designs which are clearly possible.","start":3687.488,"stop":3696.445,"duration":8.96},{"text":"They are the types of designs that are used through out the interstate highway system and clearly possible here.","start":3696.445,"stop":3704.608,"duration":8.16},{"text":"And that there is no basis -- I don't know on what basis they can possibly say that they were impossible in terms of the statute, but we'll prove they certainly were possible.","start":3704.608,"stop":3715.86,"duration":11.25}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact Mr. Vardaman you don't question that these are the signatures of Secretary Volpe or Boyd, do you?","start":3715.86,"stop":3721.065,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":3721.065,"stop":3722.113,"duration":1.05},{"text":"I have no ground of which to question that.","start":3722.113,"stop":3723.853,"duration":1.74},{"text":"No I simply say --","start":3723.853,"stop":3724.72,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You are rights are proper and so on.","start":3724.72,"stop":3726.489,"duration":1.77},{"text":"These are genuine.","start":3726.489,"stop":3727.002,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't have the authenticity on these pieces of paper.","start":3727.002,"stop":3731.412,"duration":4.41},{"text":"I merely say that I think we would have evidence to contradict it.","start":3731.412,"stop":3734.435,"duration":3.02},{"text":"Furthermore there was a reference made to the legislative history.","start":3734.435,"stop":3738.684,"duration":4.25},{"text":"I think that's a misnomer.","start":3738.684,"stop":3740.291,"duration":1.61},{"text":"For the legislative materials to which the Solicitor General refers, are not history at all.","start":3740.291,"stop":3746.123,"duration":5.83},{"text":"Those are materials that were created or put in the congressional record over year after the the statute was passed.","start":3746.123,"stop":3752.668,"duration":6.55},{"text":"This statute was passed I believe by the 89th Congress in 1966, and all of the materials to which he refers are the materials taken from the 90th Congress in 1968, hardly we submit legislative history.","start":3752.668,"stop":3766.954,"duration":14.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In a developing field do you suggest that what they said two years later is not relevant?","start":3766.954,"stop":3775.204,"duration":8.25}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suggest that it is not relevant Your Honor, because I think that we pointed out in our brief, those statements were made generally by people who opposed this statute in the beginning, who tried to amend it to weaken the statute and in fact the secretary of transportation opposed any amendment.","start":3775.204,"stop":3791.783,"duration":16.58},{"text":"So they were in effect efforts to cut down the force of this statute on the floor of the Congress.","start":3791.783,"stop":3798.917,"duration":7.13},{"text":"We submit the statute is clear on its face (Inaudible) interpreting by looking at the statute.","start":3798.917,"stop":3804.969,"duration":6.05},{"text":"Finally, I would say to Your Honors that this case is not only important to my clients, the petitioners in this case, but the people of Memphis.","start":3804.969,"stop":3812.973,"duration":8},{"text":"This case has great importance to the people of this nation.","start":3812.973,"stop":3816.231,"duration":3.26},{"text":"The importance of this statute is one which will drastically effect at least the battle to preserve this nation's environment against projects such as that involved here.","start":3816.231,"stop":3827.024,"duration":10.79},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3827.024,"stop":3827.76,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Vardaman, Mr. Solicitor General, Mr. Hanover.","start":3827.76,"stop":3831.034,"duration":3.27},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3831.034,"stop":3833.101,"duration":2.07}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 07, 1970","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger2/oral_argument_audio/17188","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The case of Citizens to Preserve Overton Park against Secretary Volpe.","start":0,"stop":9.725,"duration":9.73},{"text":"Mr. Vardaman, you may proceed whenever you are ready.","start":9.725,"stop":13.438,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":13.438,"stop":17.115,"duration":3.68},{"text":"This case is here today on an application for stay, pending the filing of a petition for writ of certiorari.","start":17.115,"stop":24.675,"duration":7.56},{"text":"We seek an application to stay the respondents in this case, the Secretary of Transportation and the Commissioner and the Department of Highways of the State of Tennessee, from authorizing the beginning of construction of a six-lane interstate highway which will pass through Overton Park, a large public park located in Memphis, Tennessee.","start":24.675,"stop":48.122,"duration":23.45},{"text":"If this stay is not granted, the respondents will authorize construction, and that construction will proceed before this Court has an opportunity to act on a petition for certiorari.","start":48.122,"stop":60.985,"duration":12.86},{"text":"That construction will inflict grave and irreparable damage to the park.","start":60.985,"stop":65.77,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"When is the latest date for filing a petition for certiorari?","start":65.77,"stop":69.581,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor I think we have until the January 28, I believe, towards the end of January.","start":69.581,"stop":76.295,"duration":6.71},{"text":"However, as we suggested in the brief which we've filed, we are willing to have the Court act upon these papers as the petition for certiorari.","start":76.295,"stop":86.756,"duration":10.46},{"text":"We can meet the formal requirements by filing the petition with the Court.","start":86.756,"stop":90.756,"duration":4},{"text":"We are ready to proceed immediately.","start":90.756,"stop":93.539,"duration":2.78},{"text":"We have not filed a petition thus far because there is the threat, if the stay is not granted proportions of the case maybe mooting.","start":93.539,"stop":100.869,"duration":7.33},{"text":"We're willing to proceed immediately with the filing of the petition.","start":100.869,"stop":103.685,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And to corporate with any expedited schedule would be --","start":103.685,"stop":107.606,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":107.606,"stop":107.863,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that might be a suggested.","start":107.863,"stop":109.336,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, that's correct.","start":109.336,"stop":112.019,"duration":2.68},{"text":"If the respondents are permitted to proceed with this construction, they may likely moot this case.","start":112.019,"stop":118.699,"duration":6.68},{"text":"If they do, they would have been successful without ever having filed an answer to the petitioner's complaint, without putting one witness on the witness stand, without having one of their officials subject to examination by deposition, but instead on a basis, out of court, the litigation affidavits, filed in support of a motion for summary judgment, that's the record in this case.","start":118.699,"stop":142.629,"duration":23.93},{"text":"So, the decision below is based solely on affidavits.","start":142.629,"stop":146.744,"duration":4.12},{"text":"The District Court granted summary judgment which was affirmed by the Court of Appeals.","start":146.744,"stop":152.952,"duration":6.21},{"text":"This case arises under a statute passed in 1966 which articulates a national policy for preserving park lands, recreation areas, historic sites, waterfowl and wildlife refuges.","start":152.952,"stop":168.549,"duration":15.6},{"text":"That statute provides that the Secretary of Transportation shall not approve any project which affects a parkland or recreation area, unless there are no feasible and prudent alternatives, or unless the design of the project includes all possible planning to minimize harm.","start":168.549,"stop":190.379,"duration":21.83},{"text":"The park which is involved in this case is a large 342 acre public park located in Memphis, Tennessee.","start":190.379,"stop":200.146,"duration":9.77},{"text":"It has within it approximately a 170-acres of Woodland Forest.","start":200.146,"stop":207.074,"duration":6.93},{"text":"As of 1965, it's constituted one-half, of the City of Memphis; Memphis's woodland Forest.","start":207.074,"stop":213.697,"duration":6.62},{"text":"If this highway goes through that part of the park, according to Department of Interior officials who proposed this project, there will be very little left of the Woodland park.","start":213.697,"stop":223.543,"duration":9.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I interrupt you a moment to go back to the question that my brother Stewart asked you.","start":223.543,"stop":228.717,"duration":5.17},{"text":"As far as you're concerned, are you willing to treat this argument as an argument on the merits to distinguish on mere application per se?","start":228.717,"stop":237.987,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor we're willing, yes, we are willing to treat this argument as an argument on the merits as well.","start":237.987,"stop":242.506,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I see that when I read your papers.","start":242.506,"stop":244.138,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we are -- we are -- if the the Court would like to consider this as an argument on the merit, we're willing to have it treated that.","start":244.138,"stop":251.937,"duration":7.8},{"text":"This highway project involves a construction of the six-lane interstate highway with the right of way between 250 feet and 450 feet wide.","start":251.937,"stop":262.099,"duration":10.16},{"text":"As it proceeds through the wooded area of the park, if it's constructed, as it's presently planned, it will take a swath of 450 feet out of the wooded section, and pass through a small picturesque lake and a pond.","start":262.099,"stop":277.988,"duration":15.89},{"text":"It will pass immediately adjacent to the zoo, and it will be a literal barrier to either side of the park.","start":277.988,"stop":284.177,"duration":6.19},{"text":"It'll literally cut this park in two.","start":284.177,"stop":287.46,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the 450 feet conceded, that's a 150 yards, if my mathematics is correct?","start":287.46,"stop":293.75,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is Your Honor, I think that's an undisputed fact that on this record.","start":293.75,"stop":299.829,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And is it undisputed that to depress this highway was going to cost 20 some million dollars, just to depress, as distinguished from tunneling?","start":299.829,"stop":310.051,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, the figures in this record are that to tunnel it and they suggest two types of tunnels, it would cost, they estimate, they don't have any calculations, they are estimates, would cost up to $40 million.","start":310.051,"stop":324.022,"duration":13.97},{"text":"There is however, a suggestion that was made by the Department of Interior officials for fully depressed ground which would not be a tunnel, and there are no cost figures on that design.","start":324.022,"stop":336.465,"duration":12.44}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought that someone tossed in a figure of $20 million in relation to --","start":336.465,"stop":339.969,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think there is an estimate of $40 million but that involves first fully depressing and then totally covering it.","start":339.969,"stop":347.881,"duration":7.91},{"text":"What is known as I understand is a cut-and-covered tunnel.","start":347.881,"stop":351.004,"duration":3.12},{"text":"But, if you simply depressed it all the way through the park, that would minimize harm to the park, but there are no cost figures on that.","start":351.004,"stop":359.381,"duration":8.38},{"text":"And my point, incidentally they have raised an objection that this would create certain drainage problems within -- there's a small creek which runs through the park, and they maintain that this -- it can't go pass that creek where the depressed ground.","start":359.381,"stop":372.636,"duration":13.26},{"text":"There are affidavits on file, in this case which suggest that difficulty could be overcome by standard engineering techniques which are use in the interstate system, just today, have been in use in the interstate system for sometime, if they refused to use them in this case.","start":372.636,"stop":389.662,"duration":17.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the acreage of the park?","start":389.662,"stop":391.612,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The acreage of the park is Your Honor is 342 acres.","start":391.612,"stop":395.955,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How much of it would be taken?","start":395.955,"stop":397.507,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"26 centrally located acres, would be taken.","start":397.507,"stop":403.262,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As I read the papers last week, the plans are to depress the highway except where it crosses the stream.","start":403.262,"stop":410.209,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":410.209,"stop":410.663,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Where they say it has cross a grade in order to eliminate drainage problem.","start":410.663,"stop":413.664,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor, but the problem with that is, is that the stream is only slightly west of the center of the park and they actually go above grade at that point.","start":413.664,"stop":422.744,"duration":9.08},{"text":"So, although they depress it in the Eastern part of the park, as it rises to that portion of above grade for a substantial part of it's nearly at grade and you have to --","start":422.744,"stop":433.383,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's an east-west highway, is it?","start":433.383,"stop":434.981,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":434.981,"stop":436.067,"duration":1.09},{"text":"This is part of a Cross Continental East-west interstate.","start":436.067,"stop":438.965,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"East-west and the park lies in the westward part of Memphis.","start":438.965,"stop":443.239,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The park lies practically in the middle of the city, if you look at the map of Memphis.","start":443.239,"stop":447.118,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Western Memphis is the Mississippi river.","start":447.118,"stop":449.049,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":449.049,"stop":450.467,"duration":1.42},{"text":"This park is practically in the middle of the city.","start":450.467,"stop":454.021,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's where the zoo is.","start":454.021,"stop":455.95,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":455.95,"stop":456.438,"duration":0.49},{"text":"The zoo – and this highway will run adjacent to the southern boundary of the zoo.","start":456.438,"stop":464.195,"duration":7.76},{"text":"This highway was approved in November 1969.","start":464.195,"stop":469.349,"duration":5.15},{"text":"This action was filed immediately thereafter.","start":469.349,"stop":472.921,"duration":3.57},{"text":"Prior to the time this highway was approved there was a study of several alternative routes, one which would swing immediately to the north of the park, and one which would swing immediately to the south of the park.","start":472.921,"stop":486.028,"duration":13.11},{"text":"And it's my understanding that Mr. Reynolds will bring a map in the Court during his argument.","start":486.028,"stop":491.676,"duration":5.65},{"text":"He'll show you the bands on the map, where these alternatives would go.","start":491.676,"stop":497.817,"duration":6.14},{"text":"Now, in the Department of Transportation, in the Secretary's papers which are on file, he's maintained that those alternatives were rejected because of large displacement of persons and businesses.","start":497.817,"stop":510.222,"duration":12.4},{"text":"In his affidavit, he gives you some statistics, as to the number of people who'd be displaced by the route which goes to North and that which goes to the South.","start":510.222,"stop":520.011,"duration":9.79},{"text":"What he doesn't give you in the affidavit is the number of people who'd be adversely affected not only in the use of the park but in their home's and businesses by the route which uses the park.","start":520.011,"stop":531.086,"duration":11.08},{"text":"And when you search the record further and find those statistics, they demonstrate that the alternative to the North of the park which he rejected actually either displaces more people from their homes or adversely affects people in their businesses or schools.","start":531.086,"stop":547.193,"duration":16.11},{"text":"So, the test which he asserts, he's applied in this case, was mis-applied, if the test is the number of people who'd be adversely affected, or the number of people who will be displaced from their homes.","start":547.193,"stop":562.25,"duration":15.06},{"text":"The route to the North according to their own calculation will either displace or adversely affect 2386 people and route through the park according to their own figures, will adversely affect to displace 2607 people, actually more people than the route to the North.","start":562.25,"stop":583.827,"duration":21.58},{"text":"And this is the case, even though in their calculation they've made no allowance for the people, they've not counted as adversely affected people who use the park.","start":583.827,"stop":594.101,"duration":10.27},{"text":"For instance, over a million people a year use this zoo, and they haven't calculated the effect on those people.","start":594.101,"stop":601.275,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Further more this --","start":601.275,"stop":602.669,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"How would calculate that Mr. Vardaman?","start":602.669,"stop":605.123,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor --","start":605.123,"stop":605.765,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"They won't stop using the park, will they?","start":605.765,"stop":609.072,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Some of them may stop using the park, some of them may not but one of the problems in trying to use mathematical formulas in a dispute of this kind is that it's difficult to quantify the values of a parkland, and that's what the one of the reasons this statute was passed.","start":609.072,"stop":625.338,"duration":16.27},{"text":"Decisions have been made on locating kind of ways on the basis of cost and residences dislocated, and where you have decisions to made that way, it was the values of the parkland, the aesthetic values, the recreational values were often overlooked and that was one of the motivating forces for passage of this Act.","start":625.338,"stop":645.61,"duration":20.27}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Approximately when was all the clearance to the approaches completed, a year ago, two years ago, how long?","start":645.61,"stop":653.954,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's hard, the record -- the record shows that that construction began in 1967.","start":653.954,"stop":661.626,"duration":7.67},{"text":"They authorized to the acquisition the right-of-way.","start":661.626,"stop":665.1,"duration":3.47},{"text":"They began to acquire it also by parcel.","start":665.1,"stop":667.471,"duration":2.37},{"text":"By 1968 the record shows that much of it had been acquired.","start":667.471,"stop":672.252,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well at that time it was reasonably clear that there were going through the park?","start":672.252,"stop":677.122,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No Your Honor at that time the Secretary of Transportation, in a letter to the President of citizens to preserve Overton Park stated that the Federal highway administrator had told the Memphis city council in the April of 1968 that the Department of transportation has no final decision from the location of this highway.","start":677.122,"stop":698.358,"duration":21.24}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"When it was clear that it -- the route would go through the park approximately?","start":698.358,"stop":702.86,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's one of the difficulties of this case.","start":702.86,"stop":705.212,"duration":2.35},{"text":"The final decision which made in 1969, November of 1969, a previous decision that whether that was a type of decision that couldn't have been changed, is simply is not clear from this record.","start":705.212,"stop":717.291,"duration":12.08},{"text":"At that time --","start":717.291,"stop":717.368,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"At that stage in 1969 November, would a declaratory judgment and the injunction had been an available remedy in your view?","start":717.368,"stop":726.673,"duration":9.3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly would have, that's exactly what we saw, declaratory injunction -- the declaratory judgment and injunction.","start":726.673,"stop":736.63,"duration":9.96},{"text":"I understand it Your Honor, it is trouble by the point of granting an injunction against this highway where there has been clearing of this right-of-way up to the park, but I think it's important to bear in mind the sequence of a events here.","start":736.63,"stop":750.556,"duration":13.93},{"text":"They began clearing that right away fully two years before any final decision was made, and much of it was acquired at the time the Department of Transportation was saying we have no final decision on this matter.","start":750.556,"stop":762.873,"duration":12.32},{"text":"That if the Secretary is to be allowed thwart any review of his decisions by this piecemeal acquisition of right-of-way of right up to the park, then the administration and the effectiveness of the statute, is whittled away.","start":762.873,"stop":779.177,"duration":16.3},{"text":"Because every time he has a controversy of project, it will be possible to box himself in, or box according to present you with a (Inaudible), simply by acquiring the right-of-way right to the park, before he ever approves the park which involves the park.","start":779.177,"stop":796.584,"duration":17.41},{"text":"And I would point that it's only once he approves that segment that citizens have a cause of action under the statute, under which this action was brought.","start":796.584,"stop":807.975,"duration":11.39},{"text":"And where there has to be a final agency action involving a park before we can bring this suit and obtain the review.","start":807.975,"stop":815.094,"duration":7.12}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's under the suit under the Act?","start":815.094,"stop":817.041,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and therefore our cause of action didn't accrue until November 1969 and we are then met with the defense well we have acquire this right-of-way by -- before approving the section which involves the park.","start":817.041,"stop":832.759,"duration":15.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Vardaman, what are the issues that you are presenting to us?","start":832.759,"stop":837.964,"duration":5.21},{"text":"is the first one, whether or not he has made the required statutory findings?","start":837.964,"stop":841.383,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":841.383,"stop":842.852,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And even if he had, your second issue or at least one of your issues is that his findings are infirm?","start":842.852,"stop":851.379,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":851.379,"stop":852.598,"duration":1.22},{"text":"Now the first issue we have maintained throughout that it is a disputed issue of fact, but we have framed it, in presenting at to this Court, we have framed it a little differently.","start":852.598,"stop":864.435,"duration":11.84},{"text":"It's undisputed that at the time we made these decisions there was no contemporaneous documentation.","start":864.435,"stop":870.431,"duration":6},{"text":"He never made a record of that and we maintain that even if he made a minimal finding simply decided in his own mind, that that's inadequate here.","start":870.431,"stop":880.373,"duration":9.94},{"text":"We also maintain that he never made such --","start":880.373,"stop":882.516,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would your first point be mooted if he presented in this court a piece of paper that made the findings that you say are missing?","start":882.516,"stop":891.399,"duration":8.88}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think at first point, I think, it would be mooted.","start":891.399,"stop":894.415,"duration":3.02},{"text":"We would then proceed to whether or not the finding, the determination was infirm.","start":894.415,"stop":899.232,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well his brief pretty well makes that, doesn't it?","start":899.232,"stop":901.549,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it does Your Honor.","start":901.549,"stop":903.271,"duration":1.72},{"text":"And let me point out that, there is one contemporaneous document, which he produced the Your Honor, and that's a press release.","start":903.271,"stop":910.494,"duration":7.22},{"text":"We litigated this case in the District Court --","start":910.494,"stop":912.67,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes he nevertheless could moot the point by presenting a piece of paper, if he hasn't already had done so?","start":912.67,"stop":917.806,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and he hasn't done so, not in the explicit terms which I think this Court should demand in order to review what he did, but I want to go back to one point involving the press release.","start":917.806,"stop":928.657,"duration":10.85},{"text":"He seems to take the position that he felt the route had been determined, and as whether he made any decisions as to alternative routes, I think is open to questions.","start":928.657,"stop":938.446,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And your -- and the second point, your second is what, is that his decision was wrong?","start":938.446,"stop":945.068,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"His decision, that is -- that is an additional point.","start":945.068,"stop":948.888,"duration":3.82},{"text":"The second point which could possibly also be mooted if he gave a satisfactory written determination, although I wouldn't concede it would be mooted, is that the court below held even though the Secretary made no documentation of his finding that this Court's decision in Morgan, United States against Morgan prohibit any inquiry of the Secretary as to whether he did make the finding.","start":948.888,"stop":973.743,"duration":24.86},{"text":"And the difficultly which is presented to anyone seeking review under the statute, seeking enforcement of the statute under the holdings below, is that the first the Secretary is not required to record the fact that he made the determination required by statute, and those seeking review aren't entitled to ask him whether he made it.","start":973.743,"stop":992.517,"duration":18.77},{"text":"The court below simply doesn't answer the question of how those who seek review or to have it be able to determine whether --","start":992.517,"stop":999.184,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"He presented affidavit and affidavit saying that he had made it?","start":999.184,"stop":1003.449,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The affidavit has been construed that way.","start":1003.449,"stop":1007.723,"duration":4.27},{"text":"It is much less than clear from that affidavit that he made these decisions, and we have contended throughout that there is a dispute on that issue.","start":1007.723,"stop":1018.071,"duration":10.35},{"text":"The affidavit is set out partly in the briefs, and it's the record, I won't go through it word by word.","start":1018.071,"stop":1023.848,"duration":5.78},{"text":"Rather than saying the Secretary made a decision, there being no feasible and prudent alternatives which he could have said, had he made the determination, the affidavit is too much is very, very vague.","start":1023.848,"stop":1035.631,"duration":11.78}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, assuming it, assuming you didn't get by, you didn't prevail on those two points, what standard, assume that the Secretary has made the findings here simply challenging their sufficiency, what standard are you urging the courts must use in reviewing administrative procedures?","start":1035.631,"stop":1055.36,"duration":19.73}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that proper standard in this case is that suggested by Judge Celebrezze below, whether it supported by substantial evidence.","start":1055.36,"stop":1063.31,"duration":7.95},{"text":"The substantial evidence test under the Administrative Procedure Act is required where there has been a hearing required by statute and there are hearings in this case which are required by --","start":1063.31,"stop":1073.818,"duration":10.51}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but not by him?","start":1073.818,"stop":1076.054,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not by him, that's correct, but there are statute --","start":1076.054,"stop":1078.607,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"He doesn't have to give notices and go through the hearings and take the evidence under the statute --","start":1078.607,"stop":1082.586,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He doesn't, no but the transcripts of the hearings have to be forward into him and if the standard is not the substantial evidence test it would be entirely possible that the Secretary might simply disregard the evidence in those hearings.","start":1082.586,"stop":1101.365,"duration":18.78},{"text":"If it's merely arbitrary and capricious standard and the court looked only to that evidence which supported this decision as opposed to the entire record, and gave some consideration that which detracted from it, the court would -- the Secretary might disregard the evidence in those hearings and the court would not be required to review it.","start":1101.365,"stop":1120.119,"duration":18.75},{"text":"This we suggest this is substantial evidence test.","start":1120.119,"stop":1124.471,"duration":4.35},{"text":"I think – excuse me.","start":1124.471,"stop":1125.194,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) in absence of formal findings as I read the government's (Inaudible) insofar as the future is concerned that the recored By regulation and by --","start":1125.194,"stop":1139.646,"duration":14.45}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor if I recall the government's brief I think that's a policy which was adopted which has been changed once.","start":1139.646,"stop":1146.764,"duration":7.12},{"text":"We don't know whether it would be changed again.","start":1146.764,"stop":1149.765,"duration":3},{"text":"We don't know for instance whether it might be waived in particular cases.","start":1149.765,"stop":1153.82,"duration":4.05},{"text":"There is some effort along this line as I understand it, but I don't think that, that is any reason that this Court shouldn't consider that issue, Because I think if as we assert these findings are required of judicial review in order to make sure that we have these findings in every case I think this Court should so hold.","start":1153.82,"stop":1174.098,"duration":20.28}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is a factor that would be a legitimate one under the rules of our Court in deciding whether or not to grant a petition for certiorari, would you agree with that, would you?","start":1174.098,"stop":1185.95,"duration":11.85}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would agree with Your Honor that it's something to be considered, but I would note that this policy has been amended once and there is a I believe a department of the transportation memorandum which is not citied in the brief, so I could provide you with the citation which states that no policy memorandum, no regulations are intended to create any rights in private proprieties and I think the intent of that is to, to say we may have a policy such as this, but if we don't obey it in any particular case, the citizens don't have any review.","start":1185.95,"stop":1223.3,"duration":37.35},{"text":"And unless this Court holds differently, lower courts are undoubtedly going to follow the Sixth Circuit's decision that he need to make no formal findings.","start":1223.3,"stop":1235.997,"duration":12.7},{"text":"Furthermore I think, it's important, another important issue in this case, is a question of whether he can obtain a summary judgment solely on the basis of affidavits instead of submitting to the court on his own notion for summary judgment the record on which he acted, instead he submits affidavits which characterize that record, and we think --","start":1235.997,"stop":1256.96,"duration":20.96}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that affidavit part of the record for us?","start":1256.96,"stop":1260.065,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is Your Honor.","start":1260.065,"stop":1262.407,"duration":2.34},{"text":"That's the affidavit of Mr. Edgar Sway (ph).","start":1262.407,"stop":1268.758,"duration":6.35},{"text":"Thus I would suggest to Your Honors that because of the narrow constricted judicial review, which the Sixth Circuit dictates in cases of this nature, if that decision is not reversed, it practically precludes any effective judicial review under the statutes on which we rely.","start":1268.758,"stop":1291.699,"duration":22.94},{"text":"For that reason I suggest that this a case of extreme Federal importance, the emerging Federal efforts to protect the environment is worthy of consideration by this Court.","start":1291.699,"stop":1302.654,"duration":10.95}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- now this statute was rather recently enacted?","start":1302.654,"stop":1305.983,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"1966 Your Honor.","start":1305.983,"stop":1307.313,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and amended in 1968 or 1969, I think?","start":1307.313,"stop":1309.53,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1309.53,"stop":1311.338,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Now there is some indication in the record, that this basic decision was made back in the 1950s.","start":1311.338,"stop":1317.553,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1317.553,"stop":1318.088,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And if that's true then I suppose the statute wouldn't be applicable at all, would it be?","start":1318.088,"stop":1322.043,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me explain what else is in the record.","start":1322.043,"stop":1323.734,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":1323.734,"stop":1324.434,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The record does say that the decision was made in 1956.","start":1324.434,"stop":1329.281,"duration":4.85},{"text":"However, it's clear that with respect to the alternatives that would be shown to you on this map that's brought in, the one immediately North of the park and South of the park, those weren't even studied until 1965 and the Federal Highway Administrator was still suggesting them to the city council as alternatives in 1968.","start":1329.281,"stop":1347.268,"duration":17.99},{"text":"And there is in the record in this case, a document, a letter from the secretary of transportation which indicates in 1968 we had no final decision on this route.","start":1347.268,"stop":1360.231,"duration":12.96},{"text":"So although, some preliminary decision may have been made in 1956, and we don't know the nature of that preliminary decision, it's clear that the secretary transportation was exploring alternatives in 1968, and rejected those alternatives.","start":1360.231,"stop":1375.995,"duration":15.76},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1375.995,"stop":1377.008,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the – can I ask you one more question?","start":1377.008,"stop":1379.977,"duration":2.97},{"text":"I suppose if you prevail (Inaudible)?","start":1379.977,"stop":1390.798,"duration":10.82}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Depended on what project the state wish to use its own fund for.","start":1390.798,"stop":1395.811,"duration":5.01},{"text":"If the state wishes to build a highway in this park with its own funds, the interstate specifications to be linked with an interstate highway on the West of the park and on East of the park and to provide the missing link of interstate 40, I think that the Federal Government -- that the state would be acting in concert with acts as an agent with Federal Government and would be susceptible to equity powers of this Court.","start":1395.811,"stop":1423.021,"duration":27.21},{"text":"I think, it would be a blatant effort to avoid the requirements of the statute.","start":1423.021,"stop":1427.609,"duration":4.59},{"text":"I think it would be in anticipation in a Federal enterprise.","start":1427.609,"stop":1432.034,"duration":4.43},{"text":"I think that any effort to circumvent the statute in that matter would certainly be correctable by this Court, or by any Federal Court.","start":1432.034,"stop":1439.79,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This property now does belong to the state it's been conveyed by the city?","start":1439.79,"stop":1443.343,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":1443.343,"stop":1444.902,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This acreage?","start":1444.902,"stop":1445.949,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1445.949,"stop":1446.333,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And the city has already expanded half of the proceeds more or less or a portion of the proceeds for considerably more acreage for a public golf course and has another substantial amount of the proceeds which is explicitly earmarked under local law for the acquisition of park property?","start":1446.333,"stop":1466.327,"duration":19.99}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":1466.327,"stop":1467.424,"duration":1.1},{"text":"We think it's highly appropriate that the city should buy more parkland, but we hardly think that the way to raise money for that parkland is selling that which they already have.","start":1467.424,"stop":1478.135,"duration":10.71}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well so you'll end up with substantially increased park acreage?","start":1478.135,"stop":1484.121,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct but I wish --","start":1484.121,"stop":1485.069,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course it may be the park that you might submit in the wrong place?","start":1485.069,"stop":1488.584,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The quality of the parks, the accessibility of the parks, the location of the parks, all of those are important.","start":1488.584,"stop":1494.79,"duration":6.21},{"text":"This park has been described as one of the most beautiful city parks in the country and I think that, that should be sufficient to invoke the statute.","start":1494.79,"stop":1505.374,"duration":10.58},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1505.374,"stop":1506.186,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Vardaman.","start":1506.186,"stop":1508.324,"duration":2.14},{"text":"Mr. Reynolds?","start":1508.324,"stop":1511.063,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court. Secretary of Transportation opposes this stay essentially because the issues to be presented are not sufficient importance to warrant a grant for certiorari.","start":1511.063,"stop":1526.378,"duration":15.31},{"text":"I will confine my remarks to this aspect of the case.","start":1526.378,"stop":1530.721,"duration":4.34},{"text":"Mr. Hanover, counsel for Commissioner Speight will then discuss the effect such a stay would have on the respondents.","start":1530.721,"stop":1542.238,"duration":11.52},{"text":"Interstate I-40, we have been told --","start":1542.238,"stop":1545.343,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Your point is that if we can confidently predict, that certiorari would not be granted in this case, even though majority of the Court might think that the Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit was wrong, but if we can confidently predict that certiorari would not be granted then we must vacate the stay or a temporary stay and not grant a permanent stay, even though the decision of the Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit might be wrong.","start":1545.343,"stop":1579.233,"duration":33.89},{"text":"Does it follow, is that correct?","start":1579.233,"stop":1582.156,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"We would --","start":1582.156,"stop":1582.367,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"We simply going to deny certiorari than that's – we're going to – it follows that the Court of Appeals decision is going to be left undisturbed even though wrong, is that correct?","start":1582.367,"stop":1592.685,"duration":10.32}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Not necessarily Your Honor.","start":1592.685,"stop":1594.484,"duration":1.8},{"text":"There is involved in the stay application, the question of whether the determination by the Court of Appeals as to whether they were no undisputed facts here, and therefore supporting summary judgment whether that was a correct determination and there is --","start":1594.484,"stop":1610.598,"duration":16.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that arises only if as and when we've granted certiorari, isn't it true?","start":1610.598,"stop":1618.717,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That question will arise --","start":1618.717,"stop":1620.776,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Only if certiorari is granted?","start":1620.776,"stop":1623.681,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1623.681,"stop":1624.537,"duration":0.86},{"text":"That question may be considered by this Court though --","start":1624.537,"stop":1626.701,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The question now is the likelihood of granting certiorari, isn't it?","start":1626.701,"stop":1628.939,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1628.939,"stop":1629.712,"duration":0.77},{"text":"Yes Your Honor.","start":1629.712,"stop":1634.385,"duration":4.67},{"text":"Interstate I-40 will cut over in part in half we're told.","start":1634.385,"stop":1639.833,"duration":5.45},{"text":"I would like to add a few pertinent facts with regard to that contention.","start":1639.833,"stop":1647.967,"duration":8.13},{"text":"This map shows and there is mark on map, only the portion of the highway that we are now considering, it does extend on out at the present time to the ends of this map.","start":1647.967,"stop":1664.257,"duration":16.29},{"text":"The route will run along what is an existing non-access bus road, which including the clear right-of-way on either side is presently 40 to 50 feet wide.","start":1664.257,"stop":1676.428,"duration":12.17},{"text":"Along the North edge of the road from West to East for about two-thirds of distance of the bus route is a 6 to 8 foot chain-link fence, presently separating the zoo from the rest of the park.","start":1676.428,"stop":1691.036,"duration":14.61},{"text":"The zoo is up in the North area and at the present time the city is expanding zoo facilities East.","start":1691.036,"stop":1698.929,"duration":7.89},{"text":"In the North-East corner are the parking lots for the zoo, which the city anticipates to expand and improve.","start":1698.929,"stop":1707.576,"duration":8.65},{"text":"Thus essentially Overton Park is south of the bus route.","start":1707.576,"stop":1712.905,"duration":5.33},{"text":"That's where the lake is, that's where the golf course is, that's where the picnic areas are, the outdoor theater, the art galleries and most of the woodland, and that remains untouched.","start":1712.905,"stop":1727.873,"duration":14.97},{"text":"The highway itself will take 26 acres of the 342 acre park, and it will involve cutting down 12 acres of trees as opposed to leaving approximately 175 acres untouched.","start":1727.873,"stop":1743.148,"duration":15.27},{"text":"Turning to the determination, Secretary Boyd's approval in 1968 of the route --","start":1743.148,"stop":1750.849,"duration":7.7}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"May I interrupt you Mr. Reynolds, could you have your colleague to find out to just to clarify it for me the outer boundaries of the park has the park now exists, I think I understand it, but I am not sure --","start":1750.849,"stop":1762.14,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be the west of boundary, that would be the east of park --","start":1762.14,"stop":1771.667,"duration":9.53}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I have – thank you.","start":1771.667,"stop":1774.489,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Now secretary Boyd approved the route of this Park in 1968.","start":1774.489,"stop":1778.732,"duration":4.24},{"text":"This was the first approval after enactment of Section 4 (f) Department of Transportation Act which has this specific language that is at issue here.","start":1778.732,"stop":1791.21,"duration":12.48},{"text":"At the time that he approved the route, he wrote a letter to the Chairman of Citizens to Preserve Overton park.","start":1791.21,"stop":1799.325,"duration":8.12},{"text":"He explained the considerations and study that went into the alternative routes at length.","start":1799.325,"stop":1805.218,"duration":5.89},{"text":"And then he concluded that letter with this statement, “Now, that the decision has been made on a specific alignment for the route, I have asked Mr. Bridwell, who is a Federal Highway Administrator to develop a number of specific design alternatives, in order to minimize damage to the Court and its facilities”.","start":1805.218,"stop":1829.002,"duration":23.78},{"text":"There was no objection at that time by petitioners.","start":1829.002,"stop":1831.913,"duration":2.91},{"text":"No suit was commenced, and there was no request for injunctive relief.","start":1831.913,"stop":1836.079,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What year was that?","start":1836.079,"stop":1837.084,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That was in 1968, April of 1968.","start":1837.084,"stop":1841.664,"duration":4.58},{"text":"Now between April of 1968 and November of 1969, the State purchased the right-of-way from a point where the alternates diverge in the main route on the map up to the edge of the park on both sides, and they clear that right-of-way.","start":1841.664,"stop":1861.225,"duration":19.56},{"text":"In addition, the State purchased from the city, the 26 acres strip for $2 million.","start":1861.225,"stop":1868.159,"duration":6.93},{"text":"And in addition, the State Highway officials held design hearings, as to what the proper design should be of the highway through the park.","start":1868.159,"stop":1879.831,"duration":11.67},{"text":"On November 5 1969, after enactment of Section 138 in the Federal-Aid Highway Act, Secretary Volpe announced, “ The hold on the project has been lifted, after the State agreed to adjust the grade line of the depressed freeway to a point as low as possible.”","start":1879.831,"stop":1901.832,"duration":22},{"text":"And that press release further stated, “ The State has also agreed to take all steps possible to minimize the harm to the park resulting from the highway.”","start":1901.832,"stop":1914.775,"duration":12.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1914.775,"stop":1917.501,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the press announcements are attachments to the Speight affidavit, the letter to th chairman for citizens to preserve Overton Park is an attachment to the Chairman's affidavit which was put in, in this case.","start":1917.501,"stop":1932.076,"duration":14.58}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Nowhere can I find and may be just I didn't look right,but nowhere have I found so far any statement in the language of the statute, whether in a press release or otherwise, that there is no feasible and prudent alternative to routing the highways through the park.","start":1932.076,"stop":1951.186,"duration":19.11},{"text":"Have I just not looked (Inaudible)","start":1951.186,"stop":1952.813,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor there is not in a press release that specific language --","start":1952.813,"stop":1958.904,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"In the press release on which you relied on as I understand it for the finding, isn't it?","start":1958.904,"stop":1961.74,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if I may.","start":1961.74,"stop":1963.709,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Secretary Boyd in his 1968 press release, announced that they -- he had approved the route following the resolution of the Memphis City Council.","start":1963.709,"stop":1976.634,"duration":12.92},{"text":"That resolution reads and I quite in pertinent part “Whereas representatives of the Federal Government have furnished the Council with considerable information and data to the effect that no other feasible and prudent route is available.","start":1976.634,"stop":1992.101,"duration":15.47},{"text":"Now therefore be it resolved by the Council, that the Council finds the route presently designated by the Federal Government through Overton Park as the feasible and prudent location for said route and Secretary Boyd in his press announcement said, that he was approving the route on -- following that announcement.","start":1992.101,"stop":2010.843,"duration":18.74}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But it doesn't quite add up to the statutory language, does it?","start":2010.843,"stop":2014.628,"duration":3.78},{"text":"They approved it as the feasible and prudent.","start":2014.628,"stop":2017.225,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"The Memphis Council approved it as --","start":2017.225,"stop":2018.707,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's not a finding, that there is no alternative feasible and prudent route, isn't it?","start":2018.707,"stop":2022.983,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"But Your Honor, they approved it as the feasible and prudent alternative, but they stated whereas they had been shown by the Federal Government that there were no other feasible and prudent alternatives available.","start":2022.983,"stop":2034.127,"duration":11.14},{"text":"The Federal Government went down to the Memphis City Council, they explained to him for over three-and-a-half hours, indeed Mr. Bridwell did, the different alternatives routes that were considered has possibly prudent and feasible and discussed with the Memphis City Council, the determination as to prudent and feasible routes, and I add that there was --","start":2034.127,"stop":2055.942,"duration":21.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was their stand that they viewed to determine whether a route was feasible and prudent?","start":2055.942,"stop":2064.797,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"The determination itself, Your Honor?","start":2064.797,"stop":2067.926,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What I am interested in is what they base that if they had – what was the standard that would have been followed?","start":2067.926,"stop":2075.199,"duration":7.27}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"The determination itself was based on these factors.","start":2075.199,"stop":2080.188,"duration":4.99},{"text":"The routes we show here, the alternate routes, are the ones that have been most predominantly mentioned in throughout the deliberations of this project.","start":2080.188,"stop":2087.219,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, would you indicate when you say the alternatives, would you have your colleague them on the map?","start":2087.219,"stop":2092.264,"duration":5.05}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2092.264,"stop":2093.178,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I will.","start":2093.178,"stop":2094.293,"duration":1.12},{"text":"The one to the South is marked number 2, immediately North is number 3 and the third alternative is the one that runs in a triangular shape.","start":2094.293,"stop":2107.117,"duration":12.82},{"text":"As to the route directly North, it was determined that, that would involve taking three schools involving South Western University and the largest high school in Memphis.","start":2107.117,"stop":2118.799,"duration":11.68},{"text":"It would involve taking several churches, attended by some 4,000 persons.","start":2118.799,"stop":2123.916,"duration":5.12},{"text":"It would involve taking a number of residential units of more than 1,500 persons.","start":2123.916,"stop":2129.273,"duration":5.36},{"text":"The route to the South of the park --","start":2129.273,"stop":2130.808,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the only reason, I have presume this suit involved taking a fresh Bill is because it was in a park and you didn't have them?","start":2130.808,"stop":2139.413,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason that, that was not --","start":2139.413,"stop":2141.076,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, that's the reason it didn't involve a lot of buildings?","start":2141.076,"stop":2144.533,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":2144.533,"stop":2145.192,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you taking a position that the cost of these (Inaudible) considered they are not to take it -- let them put it into park?","start":2145.192,"stop":2157.703,"duration":12.51}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, I am suggesting that you have to weigh the social values that are inherent in the disruption and dislocation of individuals and industries when you consider whether to put a road through a park or to put a road in an alternate route.","start":2157.703,"stop":2172.759,"duration":15.06},{"text":"On page 15 of our brief, we've set fourth, the Senate committee report which is part of the legislative history and it states specifically, “ There are other high priority items which must also be weighed in the balance.","start":2172.759,"stop":2190.778,"duration":18.02},{"text":"The committee is extremely concerned that the highway program be carried out in such a manner, as to reduce in all instances the harsh impact on people which results from the dislocation and displacement by reason of highway construction.”","start":2190.778,"stop":2205.039,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What did they say about the displacement of the park?","start":2205.039,"stop":2208.223,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"They said this – they then go on to say, therefore the use of parkland is properly protected with damage minimized by the most sophisticated construction techniques is to be preferred to the movement of large numbers of people.","start":2208.223,"stop":2221.766,"duration":13.54},{"text":"That was the intent of Congress in the legislative history of the Act.","start":2221.766,"stop":2225.061,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything in the Act, that indicates that?","start":2225.061,"stop":2227.953,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Act itself?","start":2227.953,"stop":2229.375,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Indicates that standard --","start":2229.375,"stop":2231.433,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Congress indicated it in the legislative history Your Honor.","start":2231.433,"stop":2234.571,"duration":3.14},{"text":"The specific language says that they shall approve – not approve a park route unless, there are no other prudent and feasible alternatives and the question before this Court is whether that was considered?","start":2234.571,"stop":2249.244,"duration":14.67},{"text":"Whether the determination was made?","start":2249.244,"stop":2251.519,"duration":2.27},{"text":"And we submit that it's undisputed on this record that the determination was made?","start":2251.519,"stop":2255.252,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Made and supported or just made?","start":2255.252,"stop":2258.401,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor that goes to the arbitrary in capricious standard, where the standard of review that is to be exercised in determining the Secretary's determination.","start":2258.401,"stop":2270.313,"duration":11.91},{"text":"Our position is that, it is the Secretary's function to perform to make the determination, and this Court is to then decide whether that was arbitrary and capricious.","start":2270.313,"stop":2283.581,"duration":13.27}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Can we do that without the record, his record -- ?","start":2283.581,"stop":2286.922,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Without the, excuse me.","start":2286.922,"stop":2288.46,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the records from the Transportation Act?","start":2288.46,"stop":2291.677,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Without the administrative record?","start":2291.677,"stop":2293.303,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2293.303,"stop":2294.683,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I believe that on a summary judgment motion, if there are no facts submitted to dispute or to indicate a dispute -- an abuse discretion that it is proper to determine that the secretary did not violate that reviewing standard.","start":2294.683,"stop":2312.601,"duration":17.92},{"text":"That is all that is required in a summary judgment motion.","start":2312.601,"stop":2315.249,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose we found and we need it to get it.","start":2315.249,"stop":2319.985,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"The administrative record is not part of the record in this case.","start":2319.985,"stop":2323.005,"duration":3.02},{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2323.005,"stop":2323.511,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it available?","start":2323.511,"stop":2325.294,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is available.","start":2325.294,"stop":2326.831,"duration":1.54},{"text":"It was in the Department of Transportation, it was shown to petitioner's counsel and he examined the administrative record and sold the entire record on which the Secretary based his opinion.","start":2326.831,"stop":2339.963,"duration":13.13},{"text":"Now, there is a allegation made that their additional documents in Tennessee.","start":2339.963,"stop":2345.712,"duration":5.75},{"text":"And that is very well true, but they did not, they were not considered by the Secretary and did not form a part of the administrative record on which the Secretary based his decision.","start":2345.712,"stop":2357.505,"duration":11.79},{"text":"Moreover --","start":2357.505,"stop":2357.764,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"All we on that is the statement of the Secretary.","start":2357.764,"stop":2362.255,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"You have the statement of the Secretary that the determinations were indeed made and you have the affidavits showing the different reasons why alternate routes were rejected.","start":2362.255,"stop":2373.272,"duration":11.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Again is there any reason why, the record is not in the record?","start":2373.272,"stop":2379.519,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason, Your Honor is that, that it was decided below on a summary judgment motion on the basis of the affidavits, and no disputed facts were introduced.","start":2379.519,"stop":2387.241,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It was never before the District Court (Inaudible)","start":2387.241,"stop":2392.874,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":2392.874,"stop":2393.707,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The record -- the administrative record was never presented to the court?","start":2393.707,"stop":2397.303,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, not, it was not, but there was full access to it for petitioner's counsel had he wished to present it in order to show, in any way that the determination was not made properly.","start":2397.303,"stop":2407.635,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Reynolds how can I find out the exact time, the red stripe, and the two yellow stripes on both sides, when was that decided upon?","start":2407.635,"stop":2419.788,"duration":12.15}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That was decided upon in 1968, April of 1968 and that is in the record Your Honor.","start":2419.788,"stop":2425.326,"duration":5.54},{"text":"And the petitioners received a letter from the Secretary himself which I quoted in part, telling them at that time that the determination had made that the route would run through Overton Park.","start":2425.326,"stop":2436.29,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And by the time that the land was clear, the only feasible route was through the park?","start":2436.29,"stop":2444.584,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"In November of 1969 when the design was approved, that is correct, the land had been cleared to the edge of the park on both sides.","start":2444.584,"stop":2452.879,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And so that's the end?","start":2452.879,"stop":2454.479,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":2454.479,"stop":2455.298,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the end?","start":2455.298,"stop":2458.02,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Of what?","start":2458.02,"stop":2459.11,"duration":1.09},{"text":"The route was established in 1968 --","start":2459.11,"stop":2463.095,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What a feasible route on that map as it now stands other than to go through the park?","start":2463.095,"stop":2471.37,"duration":8.28}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no -- there is no feasible and prudent route other than to go through the park.","start":2471.37,"stop":2475.923,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then in that case the moving party here has no possible (Inaudible)","start":2475.923,"stop":2482.217,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Then moving party here Your Honor has not suggested any issue which would warrant a grant of certiorari by this Court.","start":2482.217,"stop":2491.311,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When were the contacts or have the contracts been (Inaudible)","start":2491.311,"stop":2497.861,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor they bids have been entered on this job.","start":2497.861,"stop":2504.121,"duration":6.26}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And accepted, their low bid has been accepted.","start":2504.121,"stop":2505.452,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and their low bid has been accepted, that is in the --","start":2505.452,"stop":2507.889,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Contact has been let, hasn't it?","start":2507.889,"stop":2510.255,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct Your Honor.","start":2510.255,"stop":2511.371,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When -- when was that?","start":2511.371,"stop":2512.534,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"That was in November of 1969 I believe, of 1967.","start":2512.534,"stop":2517.274,"duration":4.74},{"text":"November, 1967.","start":2517.274,"stop":2519.543,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This last month, it went ahead very, very rapidly as I read the records.","start":2519.543,"stop":2525.226,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon, what?","start":2525.226,"stop":2527.742,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's was last month that the contact was let, wasn't it?","start":2527.742,"stop":2530.239,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes there was -- the contact was let.","start":2530.239,"stop":2532.943,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Now they --","start":2532.943,"stop":2533.186,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"But the clearing had taken place between 1968 and 1969.","start":2533.186,"stop":2536.86,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I though the contact would (Inaudible) the support (Inaudible) Is that right?","start":2536.86,"stop":2545.291,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that's right.","start":2545.291,"stop":2546.38,"duration":1.09},{"text":"Yes.","start":2546.38,"stop":2547.097,"duration":0.72},{"text":"That what -- that's all I say.","start":2547.097,"stop":2548.753,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"All we could do now is to unring the bell.","start":2548.753,"stop":2551.998,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg your pardon?","start":2551.998,"stop":2552.549,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"All we could now is to unring the bell, is that right?","start":2552.549,"stop":2559.487,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor I don't believe the question before this Court is to decide what might be a possible prudent reasonable alternative route or a possible better design, but rather just to determine whether or not there are any issues in this case that should be determined by this Court to warrant a grant of certiorari.","start":2559.487,"stop":2580.776,"duration":21.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How many other parks are there --","start":2580.776,"stop":2583.524,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"In Memphis, for time being?","start":2583.524,"stop":2585.323,"duration":1.8},{"text":"There are in number, I don't know the exact number.","start":2585.323,"stop":2587.333,"duration":2.01},{"text":"The city has purchased a 160-acre park which has a golf course on it, with the money that they received from the State.","start":2587.333,"stop":2598.068,"duration":10.74},{"text":"They have -- in addition they expect to purchase another 140 acres in and around Memphis, for -- with this money.","start":2598.068,"stop":2610.081,"duration":12.01},{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":2610.081,"stop":2610.798,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Reynolds.","start":2610.798,"stop":2617.937,"duration":7.14},{"text":"Mr. Hanover.","start":2617.937,"stop":2618.787,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":2618.787,"stop":2623.365,"duration":4.58},{"text":"On behalf of the State of Tennessee I think that I might for a moment digress and help possibly answer some factual questions that members of the Court have asked which of course are very difficult for Reynolds to ask.","start":2623.365,"stop":2634.906,"duration":11.54},{"text":"He having not had an opportunity to see the park I live there.","start":2634.906,"stop":2638.718,"duration":3.81},{"text":"An answer to the question a moment ago, how many parks are in Memphis State?","start":2638.718,"stop":2643.882,"duration":5.16},{"text":"The record shows that the city of Memphis at the present time has some 47,000 acres of parks within it's borders.","start":2643.882,"stop":2652.134,"duration":8.25},{"text":"We are talking of course about 26 acres out of a 340 or 50 acre park.","start":2652.134,"stop":2659.604,"duration":7.47},{"text":"Of course, it should it be pointed out to the Court that the zoo has always been a separate entity from the park itself.","start":2659.604,"stop":2667.982,"duration":8.38}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Hanover, don't get too far from the microphone.","start":2667.982,"stop":2670.838,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2670.838,"stop":2671.178,"duration":0.34},{"text":"I might have that point out then possibly I could do both at the same time.","start":2671.178,"stop":2677.168,"duration":5.99},{"text":"The zoo has always been a separate entity from the park, has always been served historically for over a 50 or 60 years by this bus route which many years ago was a street car route and formally a little narrow gauge railroad.","start":2677.168,"stop":2692.543,"duration":15.38},{"text":"The only entrance to the zoo, from the south has always been at this point and will be continued by means of a pedestrian walkway over the depressed area of the expressway.","start":2692.543,"stop":2705.671,"duration":13.13},{"text":"Basically, the position of the state of Tennessee is that we should not be stayed, not by reason of any Eleventh Amendment issue which we have raised and did not intend to claim sovereign immunity.","start":2705.671,"stop":2719.552,"duration":13.88},{"text":"I fielded in Mr. Vardaman's brief, he possibly misunderstood something.","start":2719.552,"stop":2723.861,"duration":4.31},{"text":"I said it in my brief, the state felt that it had a vital interest in this case not only from a cost standpoint, but from a duty to its citizens delay, safety, future maintenance of this road.","start":2723.861,"stop":2738.649,"duration":14.79},{"text":"The state doesn't feel that it should be stayed for the reason that there are no constitutional issues in this case, that is the state of Tennessee has not been accused of, in this case whatsoever of violating anyone's constitutional rights and the statute itself does not run to the state of Tennessee.","start":2738.649,"stop":2758.027,"duration":19.38},{"text":"It only places a burden upon the secretary of transportation.","start":2758.027,"stop":2762.196,"duration":4.17},{"text":"The reason that we feel that way is because the state has expended and paid for the land in question, and all of the land to each side of the park.","start":2762.196,"stop":2773.5,"duration":11.3},{"text":"In that connection, I should point out to the Court that this East West express way is approximately 12 miles long and extends from the eastern edge of the city, to the Mississippi river which has been correctly stated as being the Western boundary of the town.","start":2773.5,"stop":2790.679,"duration":17.18}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean 12 miles through the city?","start":2790.679,"stop":2792.547,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2792.547,"stop":2793.385,"duration":0.84},{"text":"It is the only present planned method of bringing traffic from our downtown area which is on the western edge rather than centrally located as in most cities to the eastern heavy residential areas.","start":2793.385,"stop":2810.157,"duration":16.77},{"text":"Now the state has purchased this and it's our belief that the state should be the master of it's own destiny in a federal aid situation that if the route should later be changed, if changes should be made which either cause delay or a cost which the state may not wish to participate in, it's going to be left with this $2 million expenditure which we may or may not get back from the department of transportation.","start":2810.157,"stop":2837.882,"duration":27.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Mr. Hanover, at the time of this Act was passed, when was it, in 1969?","start":2837.882,"stop":2841.979,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"1968.","start":2841.979,"stop":2842.847,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"1968.","start":2842.847,"stop":2845.082,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Prior to that time, the route had already been selected through the park --","start":2845.082,"stop":2848.088,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, they --","start":2848.088,"stop":2849.145,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- under prior laws --","start":2849.145,"stop":2850.425,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2850.425,"stop":2851.154,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and had the state prior to passage of the new Act required right-of-way?","start":2851.154,"stop":2855.519,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Had acquired right-of-way Your Honor, all the way on the eastern and western edges leading up to these last two segments, or the last two, bringing it to the --","start":2855.519,"stop":2865.018,"duration":9.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And had they acquired the route through the park, the right-of-way through the park prior to the passage the new Act?","start":2865.018,"stop":2872.064,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":2872.064,"stop":2872.522,"duration":0.46},{"text":"That was acquired after Mr. Boyd's letter which Mr. Reynolds read, I acquired that myself for the negotiations with the city of Memphis --","start":2872.522,"stop":2882.988,"duration":10.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the all, all the right-of-way outside the park had been --","start":2882.988,"stop":2887.251,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Practically, the time this lawsuit was filed one year ago, all but two parcels in this 12-mile stretch had been acquired.","start":2887.251,"stop":2895.15,"duration":7.9},{"text":"Since that time, all has been acquired.","start":2895.15,"stop":2898,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Had there been clearing of the right-of-way prior to the passage of the new Act?","start":2898,"stop":2900.962,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir and construction in various segments on each side.","start":2900.962,"stop":2905.5,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What about, how close to the part that clearing or construction taken place?","start":2905.5,"stop":2909.376,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Clearing or construction, Your Honor, prior to the passage of, or prior to this case, and occurred in this general area within, I would estimate within half-mile or less or the park on each side.","start":2909.376,"stop":2929.096,"duration":19.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But all the right-of-way have been acquired?","start":2929.096,"stop":2931.011,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, at the time this case was filed, there were one or only two minor easements out of some 1700 parcels, the park being one that has not been acquired.","start":2931.011,"stop":2941.874,"duration":10.86}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"They were speaking as of the time of the passage of the new Act?","start":2941.874,"stop":2946.641,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I would estimate that at time Your Honor, that is not in the record from either side.","start":2946.641,"stop":2952.833,"duration":6.19},{"text":"I would estimate based on personal experience that I would say two-thirds to three-fourths had been acquired by 1968.","start":2952.833,"stop":2962.177,"duration":9.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think the Act applies?","start":2962.177,"stop":2964.702,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the Act applies, Your Honor, in this situation only to the question of whether all possible half of the things have been done to minimize harm of the park.","start":2964.702,"stop":2974.598,"duration":9.9},{"text":"I think the route question was settled prior to the passage of the Act.","start":2974.598,"stop":2981.188,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You raise any question as to the constitutionality of the Act?","start":2981.188,"stop":2984.58,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":2984.58,"stop":2985.722,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You agree that Congress has the power in passing on these things, pass along to say the city park shall not be taken, except under certain circumstances?","start":2985.722,"stop":2997.367,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir I agree with that.","start":2997.367,"stop":2999.058,"duration":1.69},{"text":"I just don't think this particular Act applies to the state of Tennessee.","start":2999.058,"stop":3002.589,"duration":3.53},{"text":"I think it only applies to the Secretary of Transportation.","start":3002.589,"stop":3004.647,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But you think it applies to this highway?","start":3004.647,"stop":3008.447,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I do.","start":3008.447,"stop":3010.818,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What difference does it makes whether it applies to the state of Tennessee, if it applies to the highway?","start":3010.818,"stop":3016.354,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the difference is Your Honor, that it affects whether or not the Secretary can grant Federal Aid.","start":3016.354,"stop":3025.073,"duration":8.72},{"text":"I don't think it affects the state's right to build a highway which it feels it needs through a park without Federal Aid.","start":3025.073,"stop":3034.762,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Going back to your question that was out earlier to someone, would you say that if the state of Tennessee were building this entire highway, that there would be any federal jurisdiction at all?","start":3034.762,"stop":3048.741,"duration":13.98}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean the entire I-40?","start":3048.741,"stop":3051.228,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"All of it?","start":3051.228,"stop":3054,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I would agree with -- I would say that there would not be -- the point is Your Honor that it's done and approved in sections.","start":3054,"stop":3060.507,"duration":6.51},{"text":"The state never knows until it's completed whether or not the Federal Aid will be forthcoming.","start":3060.507,"stop":3066.654,"duration":6.15},{"text":"It's more in a nature of a unilateral contract which the federal government says, if you build this road in a certain way, we will pay our portion.","start":3066.654,"stop":3080.143,"duration":13.49},{"text":"There is no requirement that state build it, the federal government cannot make them build it and when I get through, they may say you haven't complied with our standards, we won't pay.","start":3080.143,"stop":3093.383,"duration":13.24}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The 90% federal?","start":3093.383,"stop":3094.686,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3094.686,"stop":3096.293,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what if you lose this case?","start":3096.293,"stop":3099.485,"duration":3.19},{"text":"Would you say that the federal government would only be prevented from contributing to the construction of the highways through the park?","start":3099.485,"stop":3107.81,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":3107.81,"stop":3108.561,"duration":0.75},{"text":"That's our position, Your Honor, that the statement should then have the right to, excuse me --","start":3108.561,"stop":3116.531,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Just through the park?","start":3116.531,"stop":3117.717,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"To re-evaluate its position it may wish to decide to do that, anyway, it's always been the state's position even before the road has reached the end and that was the only feasible and prudent alternative for the city of Memphis, it's patterns and it's for various other things that should be considered in the building of this road.","start":3117.717,"stop":3141.912,"duration":24.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the map, is the top part of it North, the bottom part South?","start":3141.912,"stop":3146.585,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3146.585,"stop":3147.555,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Right west, the left east.","start":3147.555,"stop":3150.184,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"This is east.","start":3150.184,"stop":3150.715,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the width of the city there?","start":3150.715,"stop":3153.612,"duration":2.9},{"text":"From the place where the road enters to the place where it --","start":3153.612,"stop":3157.474,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"The width of the city at this point.","start":3157.474,"stop":3159.501,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3159.501,"stop":3160.394,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I would estimate, Your Honor, that that's about four to five miles of the center of the city.","start":3160.394,"stop":3168.293,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And of course, if there is -- I am not talking about feasible, I don't know what's a feasible alternative?","start":3168.293,"stop":3173.699,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3173.699,"stop":3174.646,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I presumed that that place like many others, could be entered either from the northern part or the southern part, to go around the edges and would not interfere either with the park or all these churches?","start":3174.646,"stop":3188.268,"duration":13.62}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the only problem with that, Your Honor, is that on three sides of the park, where I am pointing our three of the largest through fares in the city, which of course handle great body of traffic.","start":3188.268,"stop":3199.797,"duration":11.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They are already there?","start":3199.797,"stop":3201.111,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"They are already there.","start":3201.111,"stop":3202.329,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You have no problem with them?","start":3202.329,"stop":3203.982,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir and of course, the point is that it would affect I am sure engineering wise, the use of the express way if you did away with some other major thorough fare and building of which just being canceling out what you are doing.","start":3203.982,"stop":3215.973,"duration":11.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I would assume that a highway built across the northern part or built across the southern part, as far as time is concerned, would be no advantage to putting it through the park, would they?","start":3215.973,"stop":3229.498,"duration":13.53}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think you would take any longer to construct.","start":3229.498,"stop":3232.048,"duration":2.55},{"text":"The problem is that all of these people are already moved and the houses are already torn down and the state owns all of these right-of-way.","start":3232.048,"stop":3242.522,"duration":10.47},{"text":"The only other point that we wished to call to the Court's attention is that in the event that this Court does feel that a stay is proper, we do feel, the state feels that it is a proper case for some security.","start":3242.522,"stop":3255.805,"duration":13.28},{"text":"We realize of course, that security is a matter of discretion with this Court, but the state has been stayed off and on in this matter for over a year.","start":3255.805,"stop":3265.801,"duration":10},{"text":"They originally had a letting plan last November 1969, and because of a stay order issued by the District Court, the state has not been able to do anything until the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals released the injunction.","start":3265.801,"stop":3285.482,"duration":19.68},{"text":"At that time, the state did move ahead properly, in view of fact that this road has been in progress for all most 15 years and did let a contract.","start":3285.482,"stop":3296.837,"duration":11.36},{"text":"We gave that information to the court, so the court could see how rising costs have affected the state.","start":3296.837,"stop":3304,"duration":7.16},{"text":"I do not agree with the arguments presented that it would hurt the petitioners or deny them any rights.","start":3304,"stop":3310.222,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree with that petition or do you consent to that petition?","start":3310.222,"stop":3315.33,"duration":5.11},{"text":"That if the Court takes the case, it should decide it on this argument and there is enough evidence to decide it?","start":3315.33,"stop":3324.275,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not object to job, Your Honor.","start":3324.275,"stop":3326.094,"duration":1.82},{"text":"I would feel on behalf of the state that we should have been given the opportunity to file some possible additional briefs within a very short period of time, if the Court chose to do that since we did not cover all of those issues at --","start":3326.094,"stop":3339.882,"duration":13.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that (Voice Overlap) you think and to allow to take its natural course?","start":3339.882,"stop":3344.726,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor naturally the delay is something that we have been fighting, or that I have been fighting for some time and we do want to expedite it, although we do feel that the state is entitled and the commissioner too, I mean, it could be damaged heavily without security.","start":3344.726,"stop":3360.764,"duration":16.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What kind of security are you thinking?","start":3360.764,"stop":3363.578,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they should post a bond, Your Honor.","start":3363.578,"stop":3365.676,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How much?","start":3365.676,"stop":3366.635,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I would estimate, again Your Honor this is based on knowledge that I am not fully aware of it on times, how long it would take but I would estimate a bond for – in the neighborhood of $250,000 to $500,000 would be sufficient rather than a multi-million dollar bond that counsel for the petitioners seems to think, we are required.","start":3366.635,"stop":3388.599,"duration":21.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What kind of loss would you suffer?","start":3388.599,"stop":3391.348,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"We will suffer, as we already have in the past year, the bid, proposed bid by the same low bidder a year ago was $613,000 less than it is today.","start":3391.348,"stop":3405.169,"duration":13.82},{"text":"So, in the last year, cost for building this identical engineering design have risen $613,000.","start":3405.169,"stop":3414.028,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not based on the fact, you bought this land and I would assume in the middle of Memphis, if that isn't in middle of Memphis.","start":3414.028,"stop":3422.076,"duration":8.05},{"text":"The land will be wasted as much more --","start":3422.076,"stop":3423.657,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3423.657,"stop":3424.102,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- when they get through than it is (Voice Overlap)","start":3424.102,"stop":3427.13,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know what the state can do with it, Your Honor.","start":3427.13,"stop":3429.247,"duration":2.12},{"text":"The city has already spend most of the money.","start":3429.247,"stop":3430.36,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) land wouldn't even consider --","start":3430.36,"stop":3432.48,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we might -- hate to be factious, but I don't know what the city could do with this 26 acre strip in the park.","start":3432.48,"stop":3443.045,"duration":10.57},{"text":"I am sure we couldn't get the money back in the city.","start":3443.045,"stop":3445.295,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right in the park, isn't it?","start":3445.295,"stop":3446.578,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":3446.578,"stop":3447.139,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I am talking about -- I was talking about the approaches, to the park?","start":3447.139,"stop":3449.329,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the approaches --","start":3449.329,"stop":3450.257,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The houses and so forth --","start":3450.257,"stop":3452.07,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"The houses are gone.","start":3452.07,"stop":3453.81,"duration":1.74},{"text":"They have all been, they have dead land that has been leveled and is ready for construction.","start":3453.81,"stop":3462.064,"duration":8.25}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You're relying of Mr. J B Michael junior?","start":3462.064,"stop":3465.798,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":3465.798,"stop":3466.122,"duration":0.32},{"text":"He is the low bidder, who --","start":3466.122,"stop":3467.502,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"He is the low bidder --","start":3467.502,"stop":3468.542,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was awarded the contract.","start":3468.542,"stop":3469.875,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, assuming that (Inaudible) does the (Inaudible) construction part, does the Federal Government has to foot the bill?","start":3469.875,"stop":3480.231,"duration":10.36}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"No government --","start":3480.231,"stop":3480.977,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Added incentive?","start":3480.977,"stop":3481.957,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, I think the bond should run to both and I think both parties need be protected, not just the state.","start":3481.957,"stop":3490.167,"duration":8.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The Federal Government has (Inaudible)","start":3490.167,"stop":3496.004,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, we have no guarantee Your Honor that when it's over with that for some other reason they may deny federal aid.","start":3496.004,"stop":3503.299,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They what?","start":3503.299,"stop":3504.22,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"We have no reason to know at this time when the road is completed even though this way that for some other reasons, the department may say, we are not going to pay federal aid and they may feel that we have not handled something else in a proper manner, which often happens.","start":3504.22,"stop":3520.36,"duration":16.14},{"text":"They have that right to withhold the aid until the state has completed the project and expended their funds and shown the department that they have done everything according to the requirements.","start":3520.36,"stop":3534.765,"duration":14.4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You would agree I suppose as far as the Congress is concerned that there is no doubt, they have attempted to put a considerable burden on somebody before they destroy a city's public park, the whole or part?","start":3534.765,"stop":3549.651,"duration":14.89}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that Congress rightly so has required the Department of Transportation and the Secretary to be very careful before a road is put through parks and that should not be done except frankly the situation of this nature where the damage to the park is rather (Inaudible) and no facility whatsoever of this park will be hampered.","start":3549.651,"stop":3573.765,"duration":24.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it – parks as I have thought not only together the government and the value but facilities?","start":3573.765,"stop":3580.354,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree.","start":3580.354,"stop":3580.777,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought that mere fact it was a park, is what gave its value to the people?","start":3580.777,"stop":3585.857,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"And I agree Your Honor that this will still be a park just as it is when this road is completed.","start":3585.857,"stop":3591.511,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"A smaller park?","start":3591.511,"stop":3592.798,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Slightly smaller park.","start":3592.798,"stop":3593.232,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"For the roads --","start":3593.232,"stop":3594.113,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"Slightly smaller --","start":3594.113,"stop":3596.016,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the road now running through the park?","start":3596.016,"stop":3598.936,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"J. Alan Hanover","textObjs":[{"text":"The city of Memphis maintains a non-access concrete diesel bus route which around roughly Your Honor in the center of where this right-of-way is now going.","start":3598.936,"stop":3610.676,"duration":11.74},{"text":"It's the pavement itself is 25 to 30 feet wide and has a clear right-of-way of say 40 to 50 feet wide.","start":3610.676,"stop":3619.867,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And the route purposes to stay on that, that's the reason that this job was made instead of coming straight across in the first place, was to stay on the natural separation that the park has always had, and to avoid any damage to the park property.","start":3619.867,"stop":3639.559,"duration":19.69},{"text":"That's the very reason it's designed to follow this slightly raised route as it came toward the park, to stay with that historical division.","start":3639.559,"stop":3654.375,"duration":14.82}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Hanover.","start":3654.375,"stop":3656.011,"duration":1.64},{"text":"Mr. Vardaman you have about five minutes left.","start":3656.011,"stop":3658.623,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor, just a few words in rebuttal.","start":3658.623,"stop":3661.22,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me Mr. Vardaman, Justice --","start":3661.22,"stop":3663.466,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I was going to ask the government a question.","start":3663.466,"stop":3665.944,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":3665.944,"stop":3666.899,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Justice Harlan has a question.","start":3666.899,"stop":3668.535,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to supplement the question that was asked and discussed.","start":3668.535,"stop":3672.084,"duration":3.55},{"text":"Do you have any objection to having this case decided on the merits of the (Inaudible) put in the way of discovery?","start":3672.084,"stop":3679.027,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"By the merits you mean decide the petition question?","start":3679.027,"stop":3682.433,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":3682.433,"stop":3683.149,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me just say I do not have problem on that Your Honor.","start":3683.149,"stop":3686.537,"duration":3.39},{"text":"However the application for a stay do not raise this, as one of the issues to be presented to this Court.","start":3686.537,"stop":3692.799,"duration":6.26},{"text":"The question is to whether the arbitrary and capricious standard should be applied or the substantial evidence standard should be applied and that issue was briefed in their brief which we do not have the benefit of seeing before we submitted our brief.","start":3692.799,"stop":3706.373,"duration":13.57},{"text":"I believe that we would like if the Court feels that might be one of the issues that they would want to grant the certiorari on, however I believe we would like to have an opportunity to brief that point unless I could speak to it now.","start":3706.373,"stop":3723.068,"duration":16.7}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, at the moment we are two steps prior to the -- be decided on the merits.","start":3723.068,"stop":3733.35,"duration":10.28},{"text":"We have before us now an application for a stay pending.","start":3733.35,"stop":3737.884,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor.","start":3737.884,"stop":3740.322,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The filing of an action upon the petition for certiorari and the granting for a petition for certiorari is not yet a decision on the merits of the case.","start":3740.322,"stop":3749.82,"duration":9.5},{"text":"That comes only if as a when such petition would be granted now and your answer to my brother Harlan's question you concede that you would be willing to telescope the whole business and assume that certiorari has granted in this case, and have – the merits of the case be decided on what's been filed so far?","start":3749.82,"stop":3767.266,"duration":17.45}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"Sorry I did not understand the question.","start":3767.266,"stop":3769.581,"duration":2.32},{"text":"I thought he meant would I be willing to have --","start":3769.581,"stop":3773.026,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That was what my question was intended to be --","start":3773.026,"stop":3776.051,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"I am sorry.","start":3776.051,"stop":3777.497,"duration":1.45},{"text":"I thought you meant would we be willing to have our brief treated as an opposition to what is purposed as I believe a petition for certiorari, and that is their brief, and my answer to that question is the one I gave.","start":3777.497,"stop":3790.785,"duration":13.29},{"text":"I don't believe we would be willing to do the other.","start":3790.785,"stop":3794.085,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You are not willing.","start":3794.085,"stop":3795.461,"duration":1.38},{"text":"You answer his question, no.","start":3795.461,"stop":3798.06,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"His question as to the brief on the merits yes Your Honor, that is – that answer is no.","start":3798.06,"stop":3802.354,"duration":4.29},{"text":"We would be willing to have it treated as an opposition to our petition for certiorari, except with the one reservation that I mentioned if that is decided.","start":3802.354,"stop":3812.06,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You would – if the court was -- you say we could it as the petition for certiorari.","start":3812.06,"stop":3820.655,"duration":8.6},{"text":"If we granted it, I take it from your answer that you would prefer the briefing and arguments and the delay to immediate decision on the merits now.","start":3820.655,"stop":3837.611,"duration":16.96},{"text":"If we granted it that probably would be stay.","start":3837.611,"stop":3842.075,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"If that were granted Your Honor --","start":3842.075,"stop":3843.496,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You rather have this grant in the stay and the opportunity to argue then --","start":3843.496,"stop":3849.109,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"If it were granted and there were a stay I would prefer to have an opportunity to brief the merits.","start":3849.109,"stop":3854.477,"duration":5.37},{"text":"I would agree to expedited schedule in accordance with the suggestion of this Court, but I do believe if we get to that stage that at that point we would want an opportunity to brief the merits.","start":3854.477,"stop":3867.295,"duration":12.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but you don't think you briefed the merits sufficiently for your purposes at this point?","start":3867.295,"stop":3874.296,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"We have introduced ourselves only to the question of whether this Court should grant certiorari.","start":3874.296,"stop":3880.565,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So your answer though -- you have submit you want to get in before the Court decides the matter?","start":3880.565,"stop":3886.445,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Reynolds","textObjs":[{"text":"I may well Your Honor, I would like to have time to consider the question as to what additional information on the merits and I would agree to an expedited briefing schedule if we get to that stage.","start":3886.445,"stop":3902.14,"duration":15.69},{"text":"I believe at the present time that we would be willing to have our brief treated as an opposition to the petition for certiorari.","start":3902.14,"stop":3911.37,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Reynolds.","start":3911.37,"stop":3912.607,"duration":1.24},{"text":"Mr. Vardaman.","start":3912.607,"stop":3913.987,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief justice, may it please the Court.","start":3913.987,"stop":3916.185,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Mr. Hanover's discussion of the time frame of the acquisition of right-of-way, seems to be based upon the premise that this act was passed in 1968 and it was done before it was passed, but that's incorrect.","start":3916.185,"stop":3929.905,"duration":13.72},{"text":"The statute was first passed in 1966, and the right-of-way acquisition began in 1967.","start":3929.905,"stop":3938.006,"duration":8.1},{"text":"So the acquisition of right-of-way began after the statute was passed.","start":3938.006,"stop":3942.107,"duration":4.1},{"text":"Further in the press release that was put out in 1968, it contains of following statement, “much of the right away leading up the park already has been purchased.”","start":3942.107,"stop":3952.755,"duration":10.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the date of the enactment of the provision that required the secretary to think this is the (Inaudible)","start":3952.755,"stop":3959.88,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The provision was enacted in 1966, Section of 4 (f) of Department of Transportation --","start":3959.88,"stop":3964.497,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- since 1966 he has had to make this finding?","start":3964.497,"stop":3968.295,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3968.295,"stop":3968.588,"duration":0.29},{"text":"Your Honor the statute doesn't says specificity he shall make the finding.","start":3968.588,"stop":3972.363,"duration":3.77},{"text":"It says he shall not approve the project unless there is no prudent and feasible --","start":3972.363,"stop":3976.056,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That has been on the books since 1966?","start":3976.056,"stop":3977.854,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor and they say now that the route was approved in the 1968, but the right-of-way acquisition began in 1967 and by 1968 much of it had been acquired.","start":3977.854,"stop":3992.829,"duration":14.98},{"text":"So they acquired the right-of-way before they approved the project and we shouldn't be made to bear the burden of that rather precipitous action.","start":3992.829,"stop":4001.5,"duration":8.67},{"text":"Instead we suggest that what they have done by purchasing that right away before making the decision is to present themselves in the court with the (Inaudible) which shouldn't be permitted and the Court should review this decision.","start":4001.5,"stop":4016.872,"duration":15.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What you argue is about un-ringing the bell?","start":4016.872,"stop":4020.2,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we are concerned about un-ringing bell and in our concern --","start":4020.2,"stop":4024.083,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But can you?","start":4024.083,"stop":4025.053,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes we can.","start":4025.053,"stop":4025.971,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How?","start":4025.971,"stop":4026.079,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And this record supports it.","start":4026.079,"stop":4027.467,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How?","start":4027.467,"stop":4028.3,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We have own file in this case an affidavit of an expert transport plan who is gone out and examined present state of right-of-way acquisition and examined alternatives, has examine studies of this and he makes --","start":4028.3,"stop":4041.677,"duration":13.38}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) you agree that those lines a bit bulldozed out all the way up to the park?","start":4041.677,"stop":4047.983,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No Your Honor they haven't been bulldozed out to the park.","start":4047.983,"stop":4051.219,"duration":3.24},{"text":"The houses have been torn down but there is no clearing up to the park.","start":4051.219,"stop":4055.014,"duration":3.8},{"text":"The clearing --","start":4055.014,"stop":4055.539,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Houses are torn down?","start":4055.539,"stop":4057.192,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that land would be redeveloped, it could be resold and redeveloped and what we would suggest would be to go back to point in the route where construction or where clearing of right-of-way is we could use all of the park which has been --","start":4057.192,"stop":4075.195,"duration":18}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How long would this redevelopment take?","start":4075.195,"stop":4077.918,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In the affidavit which was filed by our expert he suggested that that these alternatives could be explored and explored in a proper manner on the basis of the information already assembled within 60 to 90 days and this affidavit which is on --","start":4077.918,"stop":4093.315,"duration":15.4}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Houses would be rebuilt in how many days?","start":4093.315,"stop":4096.616,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor I assume that the houses, when the lots would be sold and they would be rebuilt according to the purchaser desires.","start":4096.616,"stop":4105.765,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"All the way back to where that line is?","start":4105.765,"stop":4108.678,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not clear, Your Honor.","start":4108.678,"stop":4109.996,"duration":1.32},{"text":"This map of course is not part of the record in this case and I am not sure what these various lines are, but it would go back to approximately, I think the houses have been torn down all the way up to the park, but we could, I suppose that park which would be redeveloped would be in the area of that 1.7 miles, something in that order.","start":4109.996,"stop":4130.544,"duration":20.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What mile?","start":4130.544,"stop":4131.332,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"1.7 miles I believe, but the reason those houses are torn down is because all of this activity took place before they made the final decision on this project and before the route, and before the statutes on which we rely were actually brought into play, because you had to have a final decision on the segment involving the park before these statutes came into play before we had a cause of action.","start":4131.332,"stop":4156.194,"duration":24.86},{"text":"We filed this lawsuit within a month after that final decision.","start":4156.194,"stop":4159.43,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What kind of houses are these that have been torn down, what kind of community, residents?","start":4159.43,"stop":4166.951,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor.","start":4166.951,"stop":4167.841,"duration":0.89},{"text":"This is area right here I think primarily was a load of middle class residencies --","start":4167.841,"stop":4175.278,"duration":7.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now what kind of residency?","start":4175.278,"stop":4176.604,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say low to middle class residential area.","start":4176.604,"stop":4180.689,"duration":4.09},{"text":"On the other side of the park there are very expensive homes that were torn down.","start":4180.689,"stop":4185.718,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know the total cost of the city in acquiring that right-of-way?","start":4185.718,"stop":4192.272,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No I don't believe that's in the record.","start":4192.272,"stop":4195.826,"duration":3.55},{"text":"Cost of acquiring of the right-of-way and park is in the record and I think that's 2.2 million dollars, but I don't think it's in the record what it cost to acquire the right-of-way outside of the park.","start":4195.826,"stop":4205.293,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And to me is what's the state paid to city?","start":4205.293,"stop":4207.16,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, state, and I don't --","start":4207.16,"stop":4209.691,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be reimbursement of 90% from the Federal Government?","start":4209.691,"stop":4212.154,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I assume that's correct.","start":4212.154,"stop":4213.596,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Were you given access to the administrative record, administrative files of the departments --","start":4213.596,"stop":4219.97,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to my understanding Your Honor.","start":4219.97,"stop":4221.968,"duration":2},{"text":"I was led to believe that based on a representation of the document of a Motion for Change of Venue filed in the United States District Court for District of Columbia, that the bulk of relevant documents in the case were in Tennessee, that's why the government sought to change venue.","start":4221.968,"stop":4239.082,"duration":17.11},{"text":"I was on afternoon, two days before preliminary injunction motion allowed to examine a file in preparation for that preliminary injunction motion which I understood did not constitute anywhere near the number of relevant documents in this case.","start":4239.082,"stop":4257.12,"duration":18.04},{"text":"And at no time to my recollection was I told that this was the administrative record on which the Secretary acted.","start":4257.12,"stop":4264.077,"duration":6.96},{"text":"I think further more the question of what the administrative record is, is a legal question, but I was in no time told that this was the record on which he acted.","start":4264.077,"stop":4272.932,"duration":8.85}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This is the controversy surrounding it on page 13 of the government's brief?","start":4272.932,"stop":4276.231,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":4276.231,"stop":4277.021,"duration":0.79},{"text":"And I might add that the document -- the document which we did take from that file and put in the record in this case, is a document which had not been submitted by Mr. Speight.","start":4277.021,"stop":4287.984,"duration":10.96},{"text":"That's the document which shows that the alternative to the north actually takes more residencies, displaces or adversely effects more people in the route which goes through the park.","start":4287.984,"stop":4302.516,"duration":14.53},{"text":"They characterize that route is taking South-Western university.","start":4302.516,"stop":4306.104,"duration":3.59},{"text":"As you can see from here it goes past what looks to be a grand front lawn of South-Western.","start":4306.104,"stop":4311.409,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose you prevail on getting your stay and also having the writ wrapped what ultimate relief (Inaudible) in this Court that you would be entitled to?","start":4311.409,"stop":4324.1,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think the appropriate relief would be that suggested by Judge Celebrezze that this should be remanded to the District Court to be remand treated as a mandamus action and remanded to the Secretary to have him a formal statement on the record as to what decisions he made and why which the court, District Court could then review.","start":4324.1,"stop":4345.11,"duration":21.01},{"text":"That that's one alternative otherwise the Court could simply reverse enter an injunction and I assume if the Secretary wanted to he could come back and --","start":4345.11,"stop":4353.412,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) reopening of the proceedings and the introduction of evidence?","start":4353.412,"stop":4357.738,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I certainly would Your Honor.","start":4357.738,"stop":4358.784,"duration":1.05},{"text":"I would suggest that when we were back that the summary judgment would be reversed and when we were back in the District Court we would be entitled to whatever type of trial that we were entitled in issue.","start":4358.784,"stop":4370.867,"duration":12.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it be a trial in which alternatives other than those marked on that could be considered in your judgment?","start":4370.867,"stop":4377.247,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think it should be Your Honor.","start":4377.247,"stop":4379.413,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think this process, this hypothetical process, is complicated for the fact what the Secretary who made these decision is no longer the Secretary?","start":4379.413,"stop":4390.877,"duration":11.46}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor it's -- it is undoubtedly complicated somewhat by that, but that's one of the reasons that it's necessary to impose upon this – the people and make these decisions if the requirement that they be incorporated in some type of written orders so that as the administration change whatever was decided will be recorded there.","start":4390.877,"stop":4411.178,"duration":20.3}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress did easily have provided that could they not, as they do in many other situations, administrative situations?","start":4411.178,"stop":4418.964,"duration":7.79}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They certainly could have, however --","start":4418.964,"stop":4420.114,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But they did --","start":4420.114,"stop":4420.972,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"However, the fact that they didn't, I think should not be regarded, that the silence in Congress should not be regarded as provision not to do it, particularly where Congress has made these actions specifically reviewable by the courts under the administrative procedure.","start":4420.972,"stop":4434.535,"duration":13.56},{"text":"I would note that the people who did make the original decisions or decisions in 1968 are available to testify and they are willing to testify and under the decision below, we are not permitted to ask them what decisions they make.","start":4434.535,"stop":4449.57,"duration":15.03},{"text":"That's another reason we suggest a decision below --","start":4449.57,"stop":4452.568,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the secretary has been arguing about the Federal-Aid Highway Act that after the effective date of the Federal-Aid Highway Act 1968, the Secretary shall not approve any programs?","start":4452.568,"stop":4466.969,"duration":14.4}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's that's a correct statement of the Section 138 of the Federal-Aid Highway Act.","start":4466.969,"stop":4472.178,"duration":5.21},{"text":"Now, if Your Honor would examine what the Section 4 (f) of the Department of Transportation Act, not as it presently appears, as it appeared when enacted in 1966, the operative provisions are verbatim with the provision.","start":4472.178,"stop":4486.988,"duration":14.81}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You have to say after the effective date of the Federal-Aid Highway Act?","start":4486.988,"stop":4489.924,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":4489.924,"stop":4490.118,"duration":0.19},{"text":"I mean that the provisions which we were discussing, shall not approve unless there are no --","start":4490.118,"stop":4495.098,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What highways?","start":4495.098,"stop":4496.037,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Shall not approve a project or program, I believe is the statutory language.","start":4496.037,"stop":4500.733,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you think that if the Federal-Aid Highway Act had never been passed, you would still be here on the same case?","start":4500.733,"stop":4509.278,"duration":8.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the Department of Transportation Act.","start":4509.278,"stop":4511.465,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And you don't think the Federal-Aid Highway Act has superseded that and gave a new date for it --","start":4511.465,"stop":4518.887,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, the Department of -- let me explain just briefly the way these acts were passed.","start":4518.887,"stop":4525.227,"duration":6.34},{"text":"There was at one time when Department of Transportation Act was passed, Section 4 (f) was included and it said, “the Secretary shall not approve any project unless there are no feasible and prudent alternatives or unless the design includes all possible planning to minimize harm.”","start":4525.227,"stop":4543.101,"duration":17.87},{"text":"There was at that time a Section 138 in the Federal-Aid Highway Act that was slightly different.","start":4543.101,"stop":4551.27,"duration":8.17},{"text":"In 1968, it was decided to make those identical and there was an amendment in 1968, but the requirements concerning feasible and prudent alternatives, and the requirements concerning all possible planning were in the 1966 Act, were applicable to this case and indeed the Department of Transportation considered them applicable to this case.","start":4551.27,"stop":4574.626,"duration":23.36},{"text":"Now Mr. Bridwell testified before Congress on one occasion concerning certain aspects of this case and he said, Section 4(f) came into play.","start":4574.626,"stop":4583.302,"duration":8.68},{"text":"So it was the Department's interpretation of the Act as well as ours.","start":4583.302,"stop":4588.752,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does this highway connect or going through the city, connect on the east end with the through highway and of course, (Inaudible) to highway?","start":4588.752,"stop":4598.876,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":4598.876,"stop":4599.692,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Which, what number is it?","start":4599.692,"stop":4601.024,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This is I-40.","start":4601.024,"stop":4602.549,"duration":1.52},{"text":"It's a transcontinental highway and as I understand it goes --","start":4602.549,"stop":4607.713,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as that highway is concerned it's (Inaudible) not only to take to get through the city and not have to get there (Inaudible)","start":4607.713,"stop":4615.267,"duration":7.55}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I am not even sure if that's a question in this particular case Your Honor, because the -- for people traveling on an interstate through a traveling interstate, they don't have to go on this highway.","start":4615.267,"stop":4628.484,"duration":13.22},{"text":"There is under construction now a circumferential which will go --","start":4628.484,"stop":4632.267,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is we have here --","start":4632.267,"stop":4634.35,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's located closer, but basically the idea is the same so that those that are traveling through can – would be able to go on a circumferential and avoid going downtown.","start":4634.35,"stop":4644.834,"duration":10.48},{"text":"I think that's that's the way those --","start":4644.834,"stop":4647.061,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Who is started, who offered this bill amendment that provides for this?","start":4647.061,"stop":4653.824,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Senator Yarborough of Texas did.","start":4653.824,"stop":4655.983,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"This improvement, widespread improvement behind it or do you know?","start":4655.983,"stop":4663.421,"duration":7.44}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"At that time, this was one of the first bills which was passed to articulate a purpose and to begin a program in environmental protection.","start":4663.421,"stop":4673.846,"duration":10.42},{"text":"That movement has been building up over the year since 1966 and now there is wide support for this bill and every other type of bill, practically every other type of --","start":4673.846,"stop":4685.006,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"To protect the parks?","start":4685.006,"stop":4686.221,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"To protect parks, to protect recreation areas, to protect our natural resources.","start":4686.221,"stop":4692.616,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand you would say in answer to a question by Mr. Justice Black that if you prevail in this case and the summary judgment is set aside, the case is remanded to the District Court, that then it will be up to the District Court to consider and weigh the merits of the various alternative routes?","start":4692.616,"stop":4709.779,"duration":17.16}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I didn't mean to say that.","start":4709.779,"stop":4711.28,"duration":1.5},{"text":"What I meant to say is that in passing on the Secretary's judgment, the District Court may determine whether he applied the statute incorrectly in not choosing other alternatives.","start":4711.28,"stop":4725.818,"duration":14.54}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The question would be whether or not the Secretary complied with the statute?","start":4725.818,"stop":4728.957,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's correct.","start":4728.957,"stop":4729.584,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not up to the District Court surely --","start":4729.584,"stop":4731.784,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":4731.784,"stop":4731.9,"duration":0.12},{"text":"No, that's -- I really Your Honor -- no it's not up to the District Court.","start":4731.9,"stop":4735.133,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to make sure I understood you --","start":4735.133,"stop":4737.37,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Vardaman, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":4737.37,"stop":4738.076,"duration":0.71},{"text":"The question will be whether he complied with the statute?","start":4738.076,"stop":4743.22,"duration":5.14},{"text":"Thank you.","start":4743.22,"stop":4744.351,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Vardaman, Mr. Reynolds, Mr. Hanover.","start":4744.351,"stop":4747.21,"duration":2.86},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":4747.21,"stop":4749.653,"duration":2.44}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Dec  8, 1970; Jan  11, 1971","petitioner":"Citizens To Preserve Overton Park","respondent":"Volpe","docket":"1066","citation":"401 US 402 (1971)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/401/402","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 2, 1971"}